name: Bertucci's Italian Restaurant
categories: Pizza, Restaurants, Italian
text: So, I came here on a rare date night with my wife. She likes to come here for some reason, but that desire has changed since our last visit. I ordered the chicken Parmesan. Now I spent some time in the Army so I know what "chow-hall" food tastes like. Bertuccis when it comes to chow hall food, you nailed it! The Noodles were soggy almost mushy. The chicken too was soggy. The salad was just sad. The waiter was oblivious. I tried ordering drinks to inebriate myself--that usually makes any food better, but with no luck, it got worse. My wife ordered a $8 margarita.The waiter had the audacity to bring a margarita in a beer glass. Before that she ordered a glass of red wine, they were out. Finally she tried ordering a sangria, which took way to long to get. Really?! This was not worth the money by any means.

name: LongHorn Steakhouse
categories: Restaurants, American (Traditional), Barbeque, Steakhouses
text:
Yes its another chain, but its better sirloin or rack of meat then Outback hands down. The service from Julie was on spot as the manager had said at the beginning. 

So the three course special was why we came in. So funny sat in the same booth my husband cleaned off the tables when he worked there as a teenager now we have been married 14 years! So this establishment is kinda dear to our hearts.

So your probably wondering about the food quality. On the food menu special you get to choose an appetizer or dessert. Well, I chose the mozzarrella balls. So many I had to share with my whole family. My husband got tge spicy chicken, now that sauce was out of this world!! 

Next up the bowl of Ceasar salad. Call me full as soon as I was done eating it out comes the hot pipping sirloin cooked to my medium-yes pink- ithe middle with a large corn. However you can get baked potato or any other side dish.

So why are you still reading this pick a booth and enjoy!

name: Corner Bakery Cafe
categories: American (Traditional), Sandwiches, Cafes, Breakfast & Brunch, Restaurants
text:
This is a solid 2 star place, maybe 2.5, trying to mimmick Panera or Atlanta Bread Company on a much smaller scale.  I stopped in on a marathon furniture shopping tour in the area and had the 2 thing combination; a cup of lemon chicken soup and the 1/2 chicken pomodoro panini.

I picked up a plastic cup for water, chose a seat by the window and the food took forever to get to me.  It was a Saturday at like 4:30 pm - only a couple other people in there at the same time...

When the food was brought to the table, I asked if I could have something else besides the chips that came with the meal (I didn't know I would get chips) and they told me I could have carrot sticks.  That sounded good.  They were those processed baby carrots in a bag...  Fail.

The soup was super light on the chicken and loaded with bell pepper pieces (my least favorite thing...). I tried to pick those out as much as possible.

The 1/2 sandwich was even light on the chicken.  Taste was pretty good, but the bread was really greasy - I dabbed as much out with napkins as possible.

I thought this place would have a little less processed everything but it appears they have processed everything.  

I did get a free oatmeal raisin cookie upon check-in and that was fantastic.  That's where the additional .5 star comes in.

I probably wouldn't return.  I've certainly experienced much better from similar type places...

name: Buck's Barbeque
categories: Wraps, Barbeque, Sandwiches, Restaurants
text:
Buck's is a great choice if you are looking for the best barbecue nachos around Nashville. These nachos are like none you've ever had and have to be experienced to understand why. You receive a generous portion of chips, baked beans, your choice of smoked meat (pork or turkey), and a warm layer of white jalapeno queso poured over this divine concoction. They give you a packet of sour cream and some barbecue sauce, but I have never seen the need since you have the cheese and the beans have just enough sauce, but this is just my personal preference. I know that this sounds like the standard recipe for nachos and any barbecue place around Nashville, but these are simply distinct and delicious. I think that the key differences are their bean recipe and the use of white over yellow queso. 

As a general rule, when it comes to barbeque I am a purist and only eat smoked pork or beef. Buck's smoked turkey is the rare exception to that rule. As a matter of fact, it is so good that since it is the first thing I tried from there, I haven't tried anything else on the menu and will have to update this review when I finally force myself to try the other "real" barbecue. The key to their turkey over other places I have tried, is that they pull their turkey from a whole turkey breast, while the others I have tried typically have a slice turkey that resembles something you would get sliced at a deli. 

 I have also tried the smoked turkey plate with baked beans, slaw, and a roll. The baked beans are a good balance of sweet, smoky, and savory. The slaw is a vinegar-based slaw that has a nice crunch and slight sweetness to counter the tartness of the vinegar. This slaw has absolutely no mayonnaise, which I feel is a nice, healthy change from the typical mayo laden slaw you usually receive at local barbecue joints. I don't have any nutritional info on this plate, but I imagine that it is light years healthier than a traditional barbecue plate and loaded with lean protein. Their barbecue sauce is a tomato based vinegary sauce with a nice peppery kick, but is not thick and sugary like many other sauces you will find.

I have never dined in, but the staff working the drive thru is always nice and efficient. They also have some great desserts, including banana pudding if you can possibly think about dessert after your meal. With just a short drive north, I promise you will find the best smoked turkey around Nashville and a great alternative when you want barbecue without the guilt.

name: Circles Contemporary Thai
categories: Food, Ethnic Food, Restaurants, Thai, Asian Fusion, Specialty Food, Vegetarian
text: I ordered delivery through Grub Hub; the delivery took over an hour and a half and when I called the check on the status of the order I had to call a number of times to get someone to pick up the phone.  I ordered during an off time so I am not sure that it was due to business.  I ordered chicken pad thai.  They warned that it was spicy, but despite the warning I ordered "medium" (one step above mild) and it really packed a punch.  It was delicious and flavorful but was really spicy - true to the warning.  If you are sensitive to spicy foods, order the mild!  I also ordered cheesesteak egg rolls and they were delicious.  Overall GREAT thai food and can't wait to check it out in person.

name: Jim's South St
categories: Bars, Restaurants, Pizza, Cheesesteaks, Italian, Beer Bar, American (Traditional), Local Flavor, Nightlife, Sandwiches
text:
Jim's gets a 3 star from me for the overall taste. My husband would give it a 4 though. He's a long-time 'Jim visitor'.

Philly is very serious about their cheesesteak and unless you're a tourist/visitor everyone is super picky and have plenty of opinions.

I think a cheesesteak needs a good about of cheese to steak ratio. Am I right?!? It was missing the cheese though. Bread was good, fresh roll. I like mine with a fried onion on top. It could use some more fried onion. 

Inside is an upstairs to eat and they keep it pretty clean. It's just enough comfort to eat, chill for a bit and leave. Jim's is at a great location so I'll be back just because it's a decent cheesesteak and is cheaper than a fancy meal.

name: Ghini's French Caffe
categories: Restaurants, Food, Breakfast & Brunch, Sandwiches, French, Bakeries, Salad
text:
This place is way overrated. They dress up the menu with a bunch of French gibberish to make what would be a rather boring menu sound unique. $8.95 for the eggs Provenal. Which is 2 eggs cooked with tomatoes and toast. WHOA! Really tad worse than a simple breakfast in that there is no bacon sausage, fruit or any other offering as a side.

Steer clear of this place. The staff is not that savvy and really don't add to the French charm in any way.

My eggs were over cooked, and they were supposed to be basted with some basil infusion, however, they were lame as can be, over cooked just added the nail to that coffin, no basting just dry egg yolk and charred edges.

Sorry two stars is pushing it when Brawleys serves up better quality eggs.

name: Sunterra Market
categories: Bakeries, Fruits & Veggies, Farmers Market, Specialty Food, Health Markets, Gluten-Free, Food, Sandwiches, Delis, Restaurants
text:
When I worked downtown, this was my favourite lunch spot.  Grab and go!

This is not like the rest of the Sunterra locations.  This one is mostly set up for grabbing a quick lunch and bringing it back to the office.  Everything is made fresh.  

They have a pizza bar, a bakery, a salad bar, a coffee bar, a juice bar and a selection of entrees available.  

I love the boxed salads here.  Chicken, mandarin, goat cheese, cranberries and candied walnuts is a fave!  

Usually super quick at lunch time and they always have lots to choose from.  

Friday night feasts are here as well.  They always have a few available for drop in sales. (You usually need to order ahead)  They have a bag that contains a complete meal for two including dessert.  All you have to do is warm it up.  The website has a few weeks listed so you know what is coming up.

name: Ristorante Mamma Maria's
categories: Restaurants, Italian
text:
We had a prix fixe meal with a Groupon, and it really went beyond my expectations.  It was just a beautiful experience - as soon as we sat down, the waiter instantly brought water, bread and a complimentary plate of delicious things to eat on bread (fried eggplant, pickled carrots, etc).  We let him know that we had a Groupon and he briefly explained the prix fixe menu - we didn't have to make very many decisions at all (soup or salad, fish or meat), the 4-course meal was already arranged for us.  It might sound funny to say that I appreciated this lack of selection for the Groupon but it really enhanced my experience - instead of having to think about every detail and choose from a long list of options, I just relaxed and enjoyed what the restaurant had put together for me.  It felt like having a good home-cooked meal at a dinner party with plenty of delightful surprises. 

The meal: We received a complimentary glass of house red wine, a salad with really delicious dressing, a simple pasta course (marinara sauce) followed by the fish we selected (a type of white fish with a lemon-y sauce), dessert (that kind of sponge-y Italian cake with frosting that has both chocolate and coffee flavors), and a surprise glass of house-made limoncello with dessert. I think we also got an extra shot of espresso with dessert but that may have been included as well - I can't remember.  

It was the most relaxing, delightful dinner -  I would recommend going for the experience and the home made food, and letting yourself go with the prix fixe flow.

name: Brew Brothers
categories: Bars, Nightlife, American (Traditional), Music Venues, Food, Arts & Entertainment, Restaurants, Breweries
text:
When talking about the brewery scene in Reno, this place seems to get swept under the rug a bit, which is a shame, since it is one of the old school breweries here in town.  And I would call this one of those Reno institutions you just HAVE to try at some point.  So when the rating level says "A-OK", that is exactly what I think it means.  A solid, alright sort of joint.

Located in the Eldroado Casino, right in downtown, they are perfectly located to capitalize on the seething throngs of casino goers.  On many nights, you will often have quite the line forming out front, so I would advise trying to swing by on off days during the week if you can.  Inside, the ambiance is pretty much what you'd expect for a place in a casino.  Pretty boisterous, with tons of people enjoying their drinks, and lots of TV's to watch the game.  Service here is very friendly and usually quite prompt even on busier nights.

They have a nice beer selection here, with about half a dozen or so of their main flagships and rotating specialties on tap.  The Redhead Amber is not bad, as is the Big Dog, which is a pretty mellow IPA.  The Corano Special is a German-style Kolsch, which is very light and refreshing, and is probably one of those perfect sorts of beers to go with heavy bar food.  Their Double Down Stout I found to be a little on the light side for such a dark beer, but did have a sort of smokiness to it that I enjoyed, too.  They also brew their own root beer here in house, with free refills.  Prices for their beers are pretty cheap, with $5 for a 15-ounce glass, or $7 for a 22-ouncer.  Growler fills are also available should you find something you enjoy.  And of course, there is a full bar and even the adult slushy machine should you be in the mood for some other beverage.

Food options here consist of tons of pub favorites.  I can say the Brothers Burger is pretty tasty, no doubt.  The french fries I found a bit underwhelming.  But their pizzas are excellent, baked right in the big oven visible at the far end of the room.  I am personally a fan of the Margherita or even just the plain cheese ones.  Food prices, too, are quite reasonable, especially considering you are in a big hotel resort, with very few things on the menu above the $12-$14 range.

As I said, this is sort of one of those Reno establishments any local should try out at some point, especially if you want a complete picture of the brewery scene in our region.  Good work, bros!

text: 4 stars for taste, 4 stars for ambience (when not crowded) 2 stars for long wait to get food. name: Plaza Azteca - Kennett Square
categories: Mexican, Restaurants
text:
I went here on 6/6 for dinner with my mother, and we were immediately seated. It started to get more crowded as our meal went on, but it wasn't insanely loud/the wait staff wasn't running around. The only time we were kept waiting was when we were trying to get our bill--other than that the service was great. 

An amazing feature that their menu has is a combo meal for $9.99. It's great because it typically has three different items that you can try--I loved it because I got to try a bit of three different things--though some had two options. I got the #15 combo which consisted of a chicken quesadilla, a beef and cheese tostada, and taco. All three were fantastic, but I will say that the tostada was to die for--the cheese melted on top was delicious. My mom got the #7 combo consisting of an enchilada, chile relleno, and rice and beans. I tried some of the rice and it had the perfect amount of seasoning. She also loved the chile relleno because the seeds are removed which makes it less spicy and much more enjoyable. 

We both got drinks--I got a specialty drink that I can't remember the name of (something with a sunset) and she got a margarita, and both were amazing. The drinks were a bit pricey though, especially considering we got big meals for $9.99 each--I believe the drinks were only about $1 cheaper. While specialty drinks are always more expensive, it was a bit glaring with the meal price.

name: Charlie Palmer Steak Reno
categories: Italian, American (New), Salad, Restaurants, Steakhouses, Bars, Nightlife, Wine Bars
text:
Food might be fine, service is lacking cohesion or even care. Hostess said if we could find seating at the bar, it was first come first served. Some people get up to leave, and we walk over to their spot. We stand around for a while waiting for someone to bus the seats. The bartender keeps moving back and forth doing his best to avert his gaze. Finally after about ten minutes someone comes up and tells us they're no longer seating walk-ins and that if the hostess told us to walk back there she shouldn't have, and they need to clean and sanitize every seat before putting someone in it. 

Operating under COVID is rough. If the bartender didn't avoid us and just said "hey, sorry, can't sit here" once we walked up, that would've been fine, mistakes happen, but to get told tough luck after waiting for a while is sloppy for what should be a nicer restaurant.

name: 220 East
categories: Restaurants, Italian, Salad, American (New)
text:
'Twas the Tuesday before Christmas,
And the Tampa streets were a zoo.
We needed to find a place for lunch,
But I hadn't a clue what to do.

(And you wonder why they made me stop writing poetry for greeting cards....)

OK, so here's the deal, a group of my friends were heading over to the Ronald McDonald House to make dinner for the kids and their families who were staying at the home over the holiday season. Since the Ronald McDonald House is located right behind Tampa General Hospital, I figured that I could kidnap my girlfriend from a double-shift at the hospital, and grab a nice lunch on Davis Island before it was time to start cooking. Well, that was the plan anyway...

As luck would have it, it was a crazy time in the ER so Britt was only able to sneak away for a quick bite. After picking her up, we made a mad dash to the Davis Island business district and found an open parking space in front of 220 East. The restaurant is on the far end of a little bitty shopping strip, and it's a nice place to sit and have a delicious, yet casual meal.

The dcor is a fun collection of kitschy antiques. My favorite was the gigantic carousel rooster that was staring down at me while I ate, but they also had an old 8mm movie projector, a typewriter, and assorted technologies from days gone by. The interior of the restaurant is a bit dark, but that makes the place seem even more cozy.

According to the information on their menu, 220 East proudly serves excellent food in a fun and casual setting which makes them a neighborhood favorite on Davis Island. Nul and David make all of their soups, sauces, and desserts from scratch in their kitchen.  They buy only best quality seafood, meat, and produce to help maintain their high standards and consistency. And, they have priced their menu to give their guests an outstanding value.

The lunchtime menu had some great options including baked Brie, pot stickers, tuna sashimi, fried calamari, and satay chicken for appetizers. Their French onion soup is AWESOME! They also have a lot of really tasty mixed greens and fruit salads, as well as a variety of soup & salad, and sandwich & salad options.

If you prefer, they also have sandwiches and burgers on the lunch menu, as well as more substantial lunch-sized entres including a small filet, or fresh catch of the day fish, chicken marsala, chicken piccata, or pork margarita. 

I opted for a cup of their very delicious French onion soup, and then had a Black Jack Burger, which was seasoned with Cajun spices, then topped with melted jack cheese and sauted mushrooms, and served on a toasted baguette with lettuce, tomato, onion, pickles, and French fries on the side. 

The "adorable one" had 220's Field of Fruit salad, which was organic field greens tossed with balsamic vinaigrette, then topped with mandarin oranges, crumbled bleu cheese, strawberries, blackberries, blueberries, and walnuts.

We're anxious to go back to 220 East and have a more relaxed meal after the Holidays. The dinner menu has a lot of seafood and pasta dishes, and they have a small wine cellar right near the front door. This looks like a great place to sit back and enjoy a nice dinner with a glass of wine.

name: Wawa
categories: Delis, Gas Stations, Food, Convenience Stores, Restaurants, Automotive, Coffee & Tea, Sandwiches
text: Thanksgiving dinner at 10:30 pm it ended up being a delicious Wawa Gobbler bowl. It had sweet potatoes, turkey, stuffing and gravy. Don't feel bad for me, it was my lack of motivation and planning and we enjoyed it very much. No leftovers, no problem we may or may not have had a few more since thanksgiving. At just under $8 it is a quality convenient and delicious food option. We volunteered at two mass feedings for homeless one at brunch and one at Dinner for those down on their luck. Met some beautiful people going through very difficult times. We joined the cities outreach team and were able to locate and feed 32 people including 9 children a complete gobbler bowl. I missed working with my normal team at Calvary Bristol where we typically feed hundreds but we all know there is nothing normal about 2020!

name: Bahama Breeze
categories: Restaurants, Latin American, Laotian, Caribbean, Nightlife, American (Traditional), Seafood, Bars
text: The only issue my fianc and I had was with the hostess. The one that seated us was very kind, but within the very first 30 seconds we were in our booth another hostess (blonde haired older woman about 5' 6") kicked us out to seat another family. It would not have been a problem if she helped us to another table, but all she did was tell us to get out. She never helped us to another table she just walked away  once she seated the other family. Can you say rude? The bartender was great while we waited for a table at the bar. The waitress was great. And the food was great. I had the jerked black grouper with sweet mashed potatoes and my fiance had the seafood paella. Great place but terrible first impression. We tried this place out because we got a gift card. Unless you have a gift card save yourself the trip and go over Courtney Cambell to a better resaurant with water view. I live in Dunedin and guarantee you will get a better first impression with equally great meal.

name: Lucky Bamboo China Bistro
categories: Restaurants, Hot Pot, Dim Sum, Szechuan, Chinese
text:
We have a daughter we adopted from China when she was 12 and she is still so very attached to her culture, language, and food. So we do everything we can to help her connect to it every chance we can get. And this place is just so authentic that it makes her day every time we go. From getting to speak mandarin with the owners to enjoying her favorite foods (like Chicken Feet) which are hard to find other places, it's just the perfect place.

We generally just order a ton of Dim Sum for the table and always end up taking a ton home because they don't skimp on the portion sizes like some places to. Everything there is so good! 

And it comes with the added bonus of getting to shop at the Asian market next door, which is always fun!

name: Crescent City Steak House
categories: Steakhouses, Restaurants
text:
Do not go here. Went with large group (14 ppl, made reservations in advance). Took 2+ hours for our food to be served. When it came out, majority of orders were incorrectly cooked or just flat out cold. 

Complained to manager. Rude and unhelpful, she attempted to allege that we didn't show up on time (we were, in fact, on time) and attempted to ask if we "had ever been to a steakhouse before", as if that explained the utterly horrible performance this place delivered. 

I cannot describe how miserable this place is. Under no circumstances should you go here. Probably the single worst dining experience of my entire life.

name: The Swamp Room
categories: Dive Bars, Nightlife, Restaurants, Chicken Wings, American (New), American (Traditional), Bars, Sports Bars
text:
I've eaten here many times since I moved to Metairie from the Westbank in 2013. I live behind the (now closed) Rouses on Vets, so it is convenient to just walk over there and not have to deal with parking.
My first visit, I had the Swamp Burger w/cheese and onion rings. Perfect medium-rare burger, the rings were piping hot, and the beer was ice cold. Went in mid-afternnon for a burger and a beer, stayed until around 8. I was hooked from day one. 
To those that say the wait staff is inattentive, it might be your attitude when you come in. I used to be a bartender, and if rude people kept flagging me down, they would wait longer. They don't come to your table to take your order, you go to the bar. They will get your order. 
The food is good, fresh, and made when you order it. If you want a burger in 3 minutes, McDonald's is across the street.
My verdict: Great, laid-back dive bar with better than average bar food. Not to mention plenty of TVs, pool tables, dartboards, video games, and video poker, if that is your thing.
Recommendations: The Swamp Burger, Onion Rings, boudin balls, wings, and potato skins.
Be sure to sample the local beers on tap too.

name: Rock-n-Sak Bar & Sushi
categories: Sushi Bars, Cajun/Creole, Restaurants, Nightlife, Japanese, Bars
text:
Food is alright. Music is loud. Wait is looong! This place is a little pretentious. Many people come here to be seen and mingle at the bar. If you're into people watching, it could be an added bonus to your meal- definately entertaining. I really wanted to give it a 2.5 but if I had to choose between a 2 or 3 star rating, I have to go down because of all the things that didn't go well.

The Scallops are actually really good. They are cooked just right and they come with a mini salad that is drenched in a flavorful sauce that completes the dish. Their Eel Roll, Crunchy Roll, and special rolls were all alright- I could have done with or without it. Their Baked Salmon which comes out served in 2 was not good. It was verry dry!! (I would definately go to Mikkimoto's for their Baked Salmon in N.O. One of my favorite food items of all time.) The fried cheesecake was blah. A few parts of the cheesecake were still slightly frozen. 

On a second occassion, we came here in a large group for a bday dinner. No particular roll or food item stands out in my memory and the service was bad.

name: Brunchery Restaurant & Catering
categories: Restaurants, Caterers, Sandwiches, Burgers, Event Planning & Services, Breakfast & Brunch, American (Traditional)
text:
Excellent place for breakfast or lunch. I will definitely come back and refer my friends. 

Located in a small shopping plaza next to some eclectic shops, very small, but they definitely make the most of the space. Cute restaurant with a homey feel. As we walked in, there was a young man playing guitar and singing some of our favorite alternative songs, which added that extra ambiance to our meal. He was really good and not overly loud so you couldn't hear each other. 

We were told to choose a table and have a seat, as there were several open on a Saturday at 12:30pm, but the place was buzzing. We chose a seat next to the musician. Our server was great, answered questions about the menu, and was very attentive. There were actually quite a few servers in the place, making for prompt service. Our food even came quick, so they've got their kitchen operation down as well! We ended up ordering the fresh-squeezed orange juice, which comes in a mason jar in a pretty large portion, and it was delicious. Not too pulpy and nice and cold. I ordered the morning after omelette and added mushrooms, with wheat toast and potatoes, and also a bowl of fresh fruit.  All of the ingredients were very fresh, and it was delicious. I've had better homefries, they were just a little bland and could do with some seasoning, but they were still pretty good with some added salt/pepper. My boyfriend had the southwest omelette and he called it a "joy-gasm in his mouth" haha. So he approves. 

The whole meal, included OJ, our omelettes, and the two sides of fruit came to less than $30. We had a groupon for $28 worth of food for $14 so it was a really good deal, but I'd gladly pay full price for an experience like this. 

Wish this was closer to our house, but I'll gladly drive the distance to visit again.

name: Noble Hops Gastropub
categories: Bars, Restaurants, Gastropubs, Food, Specialty Food, Nightlife, Beer, Wine & Spirits, American (New)
text:
Pretty bad experience here. The food that was good was good (only reason not 1 star). However:

1. My grilled cheese contained wax paper. Seriously?
2. My wife and her brother ordered the curry chicken. Which was a watery rice with the barest hint of lemongrass. If you're going to have a curry dish, it needs flavor.
3. Father in law's bangers and mash was flavorless, had almost no gravy (insult to injury) and the cauliflower with it was raw.
4. The olive martini came with a wedge of lemon.... I don't even...

They dropped a couple items off the bill, but given the overall total disappointment of the dining party, it was not enough to make up for the experience. 

Great view of the mountains at sunset though. I hope they can get their act together or cede the space to someone else who can appreciate the view.

name: Tutti Frutti Frozen Yogurt
categories: Ice Cream & Frozen Yogurt, Restaurants, Food
text:
Among all of the Tutti Frutti locations in the New Orleans area, the Marrero location is the best.  No other location has more flavor options than this one!  Others that I have visited have had no more than eight flavor options.  Marrero, however, has them all beat with as many as 20 flavors to choose from.  Sometimes, not all of these options are available (and it seems like my favorite, Cake Batter, has been in short supply lately).

To accommodate all those flavor options, the shop itself is huge.  There's plenty of seating, including big booths for large groups to sit together and enjoy their yogurt.  

The space is also kept very clean, which I know must be a challenge at a place that is self-serve.  I often see the employees vacuuming the topping areas to keep it mess-free, especially after a large crowd of customers breezes through.

Speaking of the employees, they have always been very personable and helpful.  There is always someone there to give samples of any flavor that I might want to try before I commit to an entire cup of it.  Everyone there really seems to enjoy their job, which makes me feel welcome as a customer.

I raised my spoon to you, Tutti Frutti, for maintaining such a great location to fuel my fro-yo addiction!

name: Elevation Burger
categories: Restaurants, Vegetarian, Food, American (New), Burgers
text:
I enjoyed the trip to this establishment with my son. 

He went with a grilled cheese sandwich. It came out on a hamburger bun with LOTS of thick cheddat cheese. He ate the whole thing. He loves cheese so this was a natural for him. 
He also had a chocolate and black cherry malt. Wow, it was delicious and chocolatey. We are wondering where the black cherry is though. He wanted a whole cherry. None were found nor was there a taste of it. 
I ordered a burger, of course. It came cooked medium to medium well. It was delicious and obviously fresh, not a frozen type of premade that you get in fast food places. 
The condiments I ordered were also of fresh quality. 
I ordered a side of fries. It is a large serving and was easily shared. The fries are freshly made, not the frozen kind. They are cooked in olive oil. The fries were thinly cut and natural. A slight burned taste with them, like the flavor of a shoe string potatoe chip. 
The location is clean with a blue and white decor. There is ample seating. 
When you eat in they bring the food to your table in a metal pan. It is not served fast so you might as well sit down and wait. They call your name and bring it over. 
We arrived just before the lunch crowd and  I was pleased when I saw the lengthy line that hit just after we started eating.

name: Ristorante Toscano
categories: Italian, Restaurants
text: My wife found this place online and figured we would give it a chance. Sure glad we did! All the staff were extremely friendly especially since we had our 20 month old daughter with us. We started with one of the special appetizers....the pizza rustica. It's a pie loaded with Italian cheeses and meats. It was delicious and a great start. Even our daughter couldn't get enough. We then had the sinatra salad (greens with tomatoes, Italians meats, cheeses and peppers with a red wine vinaigrette) and the baby greens salad (greens with smoked Gouda, apples and a peach vinaigrette). Both were wonderful. Then for main courses my wife had the penne bolognese and I had the crab and lobster ravioli in vodka rose cream sauce with crab on top. The bolognese was delicious (it's a house specialty) and the ravioli were wonderfully delicate and perfectly balanced with the sauce. Lastly we had the tiramisu (house-made). A perfect ending to a great meal! And the prices were very reasonable. If you're up for it, it's BYOB. This is a neighborhood gem and highly recommend it!

name: Davio's
categories: Steakhouses, Restaurants, Italian, Breakfast & Brunch, American (Traditional)
text:
After going to Davios in Center City, I thought this place would be worth checking out. I think it opened about 4 months ago from the time of this review.

It has very good food and our server was very friendly. However, this place didn't honor our reservation time on a Friday night. We waited over a half hour past our 8pm reservation time before we were seated. The appetizers and drinks came in a reasonable timeframe, but we must have waited 40 minutes between our appetizers and when our entrees were served.

I had to send my grilled flat iron steak back, since it was cooked well-done and I had asked for medium. That fix added an additional 10 minutes. By the time we got out of there, it was 10:15pm.

You may need to valet your car if it's crowded. It's complimentary, but it would seem tipping is encouraged. At least I wouldn't feel right if I didn't. And the valet in our case, and from observing others who were waiting, took about 10 minutes per car.

Also, the restaurant has an open floor space arrangement. It was a little loud with an open kitchen nearby and no solid acoustical construction to absorb sound.

In conclusion, if you don't mind having a 2+ hour dinner and can handle the moderate noise, you will be fine. Since the place is still very new, I think they have a few kinks to work out, such as making sure all the cooks are on point and being more stringent on service time and reservations.

text: Drunken Fish was amazing! Hands down the best sushi I've had in Missouri. It's hard to find great sushi in a landlocked state, but Drunken Fish has the best flavors and presentation of any inland sushi place I've been to. I've had some of the best sushi you can find out on the west coast on numerous occasions, and I daresay that the sushi here could stand up to some of them out west. Also, try to get Nico as your waiter, he is awesome! Overall, I was very impressed with everything at Drunken Fish, and I will definitely be back!

name: Hook & Reel Cajun Seafood & Bar
categories: Restaurants, Seafood, Cajun/Creole
text:
Fast and friendly service! 

Alexis did an awesome job  serving my party of 6. Plenty of on site parking, convenient location right off the blvd. 

When we entered we weree seated right away by smiling and friendly faces. 

The menu had a nice variety of items to choose from so we tried all different appetizers. We ended up getting crab bites, chicken wings, shrimp po boys and we shared them. 

Never really had crab before but tasted the crab bites they were pretty good. When it came to the main meal I got the Mardi Gras boil  which came with crawfish, shrimp, and mussels, corn cob and potatoes in a Cajun sauce. Everyone at my  table got some form of boil, with crab legs, shrimp, or mussels. 

The boils were steaming hot and the sauce it came in was flavorful. 

The dessert had many options and I ended  up getting the key lime cheesecake, carrot cake that was gluten free and my boyfriend got the waffle with ice cream. Everyone else got the waffle and chocolate cake and raspberry creme  brle. I tasted a little of each dessert, but my favorites were the chocolate cake and cheesecake.

This experience was a great one and I'd definitely come back again inn the near future. 

The portions were so big- I actually had some to take home. 

This place deserves 5 stars on service, and food.

name: Agustin Kitchen
categories: Restaurants, Seafood, Nightlife, Sandwiches, American (New), Bars, French, Cocktail Bars
text: First time visit for dinner on a Thursday evening, first ones to be seated at the table, seems like everyone else was heading to the bar, as that was crowded. In the same space, but separate by a glass wall. We did not receive a happy hour menu with our dinner menu, so can not say if they offer happy hour prices in the dining room. Service was attentive. We got the chef's board with different meats and cheeses and pickled veggies. It was good and one of the best we had for $20. But the rest of our meals were disappointing. Lots of shellfish on the menu which I do not eat, so was trying to find something and opted for the cod, which was hard and rubbery ( I sent it back). The rice and veggies were flavorless. My husbands wilted kale salad was not that wilted with large pieces making it difficult to eat. My daughter said her shrimp And risotto was tasty. They did treat me to dessert for the mishap with the fish which was a nice touch. Maybe an off night for us, or we needed to just stick to small plates and chefs board. The service was good here. No complaints on the waitstaff as our drinks and water were kept filled.

name: Varga Bar
categories: Nightlife, Bars, American (New), Gastropubs, Restaurants
text:
Oh how I love you Varga Bar.

Ok, all joking aside, this is ONE OF THE BEST bars I've ever been to.  The decor makes you feel classy even though you probably aren't.  The food tastes amazing and makes you think you're getting a deal because it's so reasonably priced.  The bartenders and servers are very down to earth which rounds the whole experience out.  It's just a completely honest place that has won a spot in my heart.

Varga has an extremely impressive and rotating beer selection.  This is due in part to Ian, the bartender with whom I'm most familiar.  You can actually sit and talk beer with this guy for hours.  His choices are aggressive and he knows how to write-up each brew in a way that everyone can relate to.  I've drank plenty of beers in my day but I'll read a quick description at Varga and think "hrmm, I don't remember that flavor in that beer"  The next think you know, you have a pint of it in front of you.  That is business savvy right there.

The food, in a word, awesome.  I realize that I've become truly spoiled living in Philadelphia in regards to food.  Any "gastropub" in Philly has to bring their best to the table if they just want to survive.  I think Varga is one of the top contenders in this realm.  I can honestly say that everything that comes out of that kitchen is great.  They do happen to have the best wings I've ever tasted.  Their wings, in case you were wondering, are so tender that the meat falls off the bone when you pick one up.  That's worth the price of admission alone.  The Varga salad, just plain wonderful.  Lots of flavors playing very well together and light enough to make you feel like you aren't undoing all your gym activity.  They've been featuring oysters recently and that is something that makes me very happy.  The first night I had oysters at Varga, I had them with the Victory Scarlet Fire.  Oh my God.  A super smoky beer with oysters on a hot summer night and only three blocks from my home, does life really get any better than this?  These are the kind of things you think about when you're a patron of Varga.

Five stars, this place needs six.

name: The Oink Cafe - Tucson
categories: Restaurants, Cafes, Sandwiches, Breakfast & Brunch
text: Just finished eating breakfast here thoroughly disappointed after a decent breakfast here last Saturday. I'm giving 2 stars because I know they can do better today not so much. Starting with the gravy; gravy on the chicken fried steak was lumpy, no flavor and over floured; it tasted like Elmers Glue and the steak itself over fried! The gravy on the biscuits and gravy was watery, no flavor or consistency in short disgusting! The eggs were cooked well, the French toast and chorizo tasty. Experience was a total bummer, thank God for a nice strong Bloody Mary! And really $84 for breakfast! We could've gone to the casino and had champagne brunch with crab legs for that price!

name: Founding Farmers King of Prussia
categories: American (New), Breakfast & Brunch, Food, Restaurants, Desserts
text: Let me just say that food was quite good. I have been here a few times and usually I have great service. However, this time the server, who was a tall young blonde lady with a septum piercing was completely dismissive with my table. First she was quite curt with us when we sat down and tried to order drinks, which took about 20 minutes. She then didn't bother to clear the table, but was quite friendly and proactive for all the surrounding tables.  I finally had to grab another server after waiting for 15 minutes to get our check. I just felt like I was being discriminated especially seeing how she treat all her other tables, who are of a similar background to her.

name: Prohibition Taproom
categories: American (Traditional), Bars, Nightlife, Restaurants, Beer Bar, Gastropubs, Breakfast & Brunch, Tapas/Small Plates
text:
We were looking for a fun, cool place to grab a few drinks and lunch and what word better jumps out at you than Prohibition?

The place wasn't too packed but did have a good number of people inside, I'm guessing for the World Cup.  It's a pretty standard set up. Tables and a bar.  They had three bartenders working, so it was very easy to get a drink.

The menu looked great.  I decided on a special though.  It was a knockwurst sandwich with Swiss cheese and an egg.  It was everything I could ever want it to be.  Absolutely wonderful.  My girlfriend got the Mac and Cheese which she said was equally as good.  We traded bites and it was delicious.  Creamy, hearty and tangy all at the same time.

They have a great selection of craft and Import beers.  I tried a couple different ones and even used the bartenders knowledge of the brews a bit.

Honestly, I don't often get to Philly, but when in town I'll be back.  I've also already recommended the place to a friend.

name: Vietnam Express
categories: Vietnamese, Sandwiches, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Restaurants, Bubble Tea, Food
text:
Went here 30 minutes before closing and got the brisket pho takeout, which took 5 minutes. The broth came in its own container while the noodles, beef, and seasoning were in the bowl. The order also comes with bean sprouts, jalapeno slices, basil leaves, and a few slices of lime that come separately in saran wrap. They give you chopsticks, plastic utensils, and hot sauce as well. It took me 10 minutes to walk home but the broth was still steaming hot when I got back, which is a good sign. The stuff in the bowl and the raw veggies looked relatively fresh, although the meat is cooked (although I wouldn't expect raw meat from a takeout place).

The portions are decent, and this is coming from a guy who eats a lot (1 chipotle burrito isn't enough). They give you a lot of noodles and an okay amount of meat. The broth was quite flavorful. Overall for a small takeout place like this the food exceeded expectations, and I will definitely be coming back for more pho.

name: Amada
categories: Spanish, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Tapas Bars, Iberian
text: It's been on our list for a couple of years now, but somehow we still never made it until recently.  My husband made a reservation several weeks in advance for our anniversary, which also turned out to be during restaurant week.  Bonus!  Our best friends (who are avid Amada fans) recommended the madre e hijo and the ham croquettes, which are both to die for.  Probably my two favorites also.  That being said, there was nothing I tried that I didn't like.  The truffled lavender honey and the garlic dulce de leche with their cheese pairings were so different and flavorful.  I would definitely go back to try more of the same as well as some new dishes we didn't have room for.  We definitely won't be waiting another 3 years to return!

name: La Croisette
categories: Breakfast & Brunch, Burgers, American (Traditional), Restaurants
text:
In order to get in Beverly's with my sanity, I waited til a week day.  Parking is a premium at the corner of Gulf & Corey.  They probably appreciate it--as they are busy enuf already.  I pulled the star for the "frenetic" noise and rushing in the place, crowded with tables and patrons.  Great diner, lots of locals and tourists, but bustling all the time. But they bring your food out quickly, too.  Extensive menu with options a notch above most diners. Great prices. Fantastic French toast on French bread, nice slab of breakfast ham, egg cooked to perfection.  Can substitute fruit for an upcharge.  Not sure where "La Croisette" comes from, but Beverly is a talented artist with great works of Hollywood actors on the walls.
UPDATE 5/2016.  Still delicious.  Love the homemade orange marmalade for the French toast.  Sausage is good too.

name: Maynards
categories: Grocery, Burgers, Food, Local Flavor, Restaurants, Salad, American (Traditional), Nightlife, American (New), Bars, Sandwiches, Breakfast & Brunch
text:
First off, Maynards is unique in that it has its own little parking lot, a rarity in that area, so you don't have to waste time finding a street meter.

When you enter The Marketplace, there is a really nice atmosphere. There is a full bar, a barista station, and a case featuring pastries. The menu has a good variety for whatever you are feeling, even for breakfast! There are vegan options, vegetarian options, and if you're a meat lover, I hear from a friend the bacon is pretty phenomenal! 

As you can see there is lovely presentation on the plate. My avocado toast was accompanied by arugula (my favorite!) and a strawberry. It was absolutely delicious! I've tried the black coffee and the espresso as well. Black coffee was meh. If you're looking for something really impressive, go to one of the nearby specialty shops. The espresso here at Maynard's wasn't too bad, though!

The indoor seating features cute wooden tables, and there is a HUGE patio outside if you're looking to get some sun. This place is really cute, and as of now is my favorite place to go out and get breakfast here in Tucson. 

My next mission here- to try out the bar!!!

name: Oak
categories: Beer, Wine & Spirits, Bars, Tapas Bars, Restaurants, Food, Nightlife, Wine Bars
text:
Since I was traveling - I asked Chef Stew what is/ar the best items on menu?  This young talented guy - Stew (great name for a chef by the way) recommended the Grilled Broccoli and the Chickpea Cavatelli (fancy name for pasta). The balance of sweet and sour with the Sesame dressing on the Broccoli was delicious- portion was perfect too. Then came the Cavatelli. Oh my stars. The lamb & mushroom was amazing- the basil used to accent the dish was ideal- fresh, delicate, not overdone - WELL DONE STEWART FREEMAN!   
The evening was complimented by the house red and not one, but two desserts that again, Chef Stew and co- worker recommended. The chocolate mousse was creamy, dark chocolate flavor- that was worth every calorie consumed.  But then came the fruit tart. Splendid! Loaded with blueberries and a great crumb- this is comfort food and fine dining wrapped up in a wine bar. Well done Oak!  Cool patio you all share with Ale too!

name: Los Camaradas
categories: Mexican, Restaurants
text: This is a staple in our weekly nights out. Taco Tuesday at Los Camaradas is by far one of the best places to get real authentic tasting tacos in the city. I absolutely love their Baja fish tacos, and the chef special is usually a hit with everyone! The masa fries appetizer is definitely a must try, and their guacamole with any of the add in's or just by itself is worth it. I have also previously worked in a tequila bar myself, and I can say that the tequila and mezcal options at Los Camaradas is ideal for both a nice dinner out, or a night out of drinking with friends! I can't wait for summer to come back so we can eat outside again!

name: Royal House
categories: American (New), Restaurants, Sandwiches, Seafood, Cajun/Creole
text:
Upon canceling our reservations at Antoines (the prices and hot/cold reviews) made us re-think our decision, we decided to check out Royal House (diagonally across the street from our hotel). The decor with candle lit tables, warm welcome and abundant seating was just what we were looking for. It was cozy, and homey, with a romantic vibe. Our waitress was amazing, and recommended drinks (the patron punch) and it was KILLER, amazing. We then ordered the Oyster Duo (Oysters Rockefeller and Oysters Royal) both were AMAZING, out of this world delicious, and for our entree I ordered the Oyster Pasta in scampi sauce and my boyfriend ordered the Oyster BLT PoBoy...now when I say these meals were delicious, it's an understatement...these meals were other worldly good. My pasta was cooked perfectly, the sauce a creamy, spicy, garlicky heaven, and the fried oysters were incredible, everything on the plate melded together to form a plate of pure food induced ecstasy (I couldn't stop smiling with every bite, but that could have been the punch). My boyfriends PoBoy was also Heaven sent, a perfect mixture of flavors and textures to send anyone into a welcomed food coma...we were offered dessert, but were both bursting at the seams after scraping our plates clean.
I HIGHLY recommend this place, wonderful servers, great ambiance, and PHENOMENAL food.

name: Red Fish Grill
categories: Seafood, Restaurants, Cajun/Creole
text:
The food is good . . . but in a city like New Orleans where there's ton of restaurants with good, great and even outstanding food, "good" is simply not enough.

So, the food. Tasty, well presented. And the kitchen is willing and able to adjust for dietary needs. 

The service, good, but pushy and presumptive. The waitress took it upon herself to preorder special desserts for us, then we, of course, were in an uncomfortable position after the main course when we told her we weren't interested.

The ambiance - what ambience? Loud, crowded . . . felt like a school dining hall. Nice commercial art, but not a friendly welcoming room where you could have a quiet friendly meal.

Cost - overpriced, considering the dining hall feel to the place. If I want to be in a crowded loud place, there are plenty of restaurants in New Orleans that are half the price.

I wont be visiting here again. For a fine seafood dinner, I'll go to GW Fins; for a cheap fun seafood dinner, Acme Oyster House.

name: Joey K's Restaurant & Bar
categories: Restaurants, Southern
text:
Add Joey K's to your list of only-in-NOLA funky, neighborhood dining establishments.  

If you order only one thing, make it the onion rings.  If there's fewer than three in your party, the onion rings nay be all you need!  They are the biggest AND best you've ever eaten.  (Rumor has it, Zatarain's makes the batter especially for Joey K's.). 

The red beans & rice are fantastic and if this fried chicken is not the best is town, it's easily in the top three, and may get the nod based on a better atmosphere, in a more walkable neighborhood and at a better price than the other top ranked fried chicken restaurant(s).  Legit sides, too.  Nothing goes better with fried chicken than potatoes, gravy and green beans!

Great service, too!

name: Las Cazuelas Restaurant BYOB
categories: Food, Tacos, Mexican, Latin American, Restaurants, Spanish
text: I am a vegetarian and was thrilled to see they had seitan on the menu as a protein option.  I began eating my leftovers today and there was pork or chicken hidden in the middle.  Whether this was intentional or not, it is EXTREMELY disappointing.  You should be able to trust a restaurant.  If this was intentional, not only was it not funny but my belly hurt all day.  If this was unintentional, than I would have to comment on the lack of organization and cleanliness of the restaurant because we were one of three tables there all night, there was no reason to get pork mixed in a vegetarian dish.  Completely disappointing.  I understand that a meat eater may not understand why this is such a big deal, but it is IMPORTANT to me.  They are lazy and cannot be trusted.  Even if you eat meat, if this is how they run their restaurant, what are they half-assing for you? Do not eat here.   Terrible, terrible disgrace for a restaurant.

name: 2nd Story Brewing
categories: Breweries, Bars, Restaurants, Food, Nightlife, American (New), Pubs, Gastropubs
text:
We had a wonderful experience here when we were in Philly for the weekend. 

We called ahead for a party of 7. Then got lost walking in the pouring rain from our hotel. Haha. They were expecting us and had a table waiting for us as soon as we walked in the door. The hosts were friendly and very knowledgable. 

We got the pretzels for an appetizer and they were wonderful!(the dark sauce is NOT the cheese like you would expect. Haha.)

Our drinks were served quickly, refilled promptly and while my husband and I didn't drink any of the beer, my brother and his wife did and they were very impressed with everything they tried. 

The food was wonderful. The umms and ohhhhs while eating never stopped. The brisket on a biscuit was a huge his and my chicken stew and biscuits were mouth watering. The kids(9,12 & 16) were impressed and even with a lack of children's menu, the staff was quick to recommend quite a few child pleasing dishes that pleased them all!

The dessert sundae wasn't really my cup of tea, but others liked it! 

If you ask the 16 year old, she would tell you about the co-ed bathrooms. Haha. She was quite shocked with that concept!

We would gladly eat there again and will recommend it to anyone who is in Philly!

name: Circles Waterfront at Lands End Marina
categories: Seafood, Restaurants, Steakhouses, Bars, Nightlife
text:
This restaurant provides a great view during your dining experience. However the food is average at best. There was nothing that caught my attention on the menu. The prime rib special is $22.99 and a nice cut for that price. I personally prefer the prime rib from another restaurant in the area that only cost $14.99. This prime rib was served with a thick gravy-like au ju and I prefer the thinner liquid form.

The chowder was decent. I opted out of the bread basket and I didn't see an appetizer that caught my attention. There is a full bar, however, the server did not share any of the specials. The restaurant was spacious and well-maintained. The service is ok, however, the view is great. Not my first choice for dinner but I would consider giving it a second chance.

name: Mena's Palace
categories: Restaurants, Southern, Cajun/Creole, Seafood, Breakfast & Brunch
text:
Plain food at a good price.  This place was suggested by the concierge at our hotel.  I have to say, sometimes the people at the front desk are wrong.  We asked for a place to get good grits.  They sent us here, saying locals who work in the area eat here.

That is probably true, because it is affordable and fast, and the employees are very nice.  However, food was just meh.  My "omelet" was actually scrambled eggs with some sausage in it, not much of an omelet.  I saw something go past that looked like Salisbury steak that reminded me of the food in my high school cafeteria.  

Good if you're in a hurry and need an inexpensive meal, but not really representative of the level of food available in New Orleans.

name: Mission Taco Joint - Historic Soulard
categories: Restaurants, Cocktail Bars, Tacos, Latin American, Mexican, Bars, Nightlife, Beer Bar
text:
This was our first time at the new location in Soulard.   This is located at Lafayette and 9th across the street from Bogarts.  
The building is very cool w/ a garage door style opening in the front.  The place is all exposed brick, wood and girders so very urban and cool.  Unfortunately since there is so much brick and the ceilings are so tall....it was really loud in there and everyone had to yell.  When we came in we left our cell number with the host.  They will then text you when your table is ready.  I wish more places did that.
We sat at the bar and ordered drinks.  Our bartenders were very helpful and nice.  One of the things that I really love about Mission is their cocktail selection.  I order the Delmar Boulevardier and when they made it they lit the inside of the glass on fire....so this is a great drink to order while at the bar.  It was really good too.
We started off with the chips and salsa and one was mild and one was hotter....but we felt that they were both kinda hot. 
We also ordered an assortment of tacos (fish, steak and pork) and some street corn and jasmine rice (I've never had that before here).  Everything we got was really good.  
I think that our server was Daniel and he did a great job and was very attentive.
We are so glad that they opened this location since it's much closer to our neighborhood.    Great job guys!

name: The Avenue Pub
categories: Bars, Beer Gardens, Pubs, French, Mediterranean, Nightlife, Southern, Restaurants
text:
This is my neighborhood pub... I can't actually express how much pride I take in being able to say that. For anyone that's remotely interested in finely crafted beer, there are few places in the world that take that as seriously as the staff @ Avenue do. The beer selection is in a state of constant flux, one rare beer keg making way for another exotic selection. The casks and one-offs that come in are a real treat. 
When you find that one beer that you fall in love with, you will come back frequently until the keg is gone, for who knows when another opportunity will come to experience it again?
The food is solid, and most definitely a cut above standard pub fare... The "To Die For" Fries are a bit daunting, drowned in a soupy garlic bechamel and onions, but it is a decadent reward when you think you've drank one pint past your personal limit.
Some pints can be truly pricey, at times, but the "Crafty Hours" and other specials they run can definitely offset the price one pays for truly exceptional beer.

name: Raging Sage
categories: Food, Restaurants, Coffee & Tea
text:
Raging Sage is a nice coffee shop. It has plenty of seating and a cute patio. I think the coffee here is pretty good - it doesn't blow me away like some other shops, but it is, legitimately, good coffee. I appreciate that the lattes I've gotten here taste strong and not watered down. I love not having to order extra shots of espresso because of weak coffee. 
I have yet to try the food but it always smells great in there.

Something that bothered me the last time I was here was that the wifi doesn't "open" until 11am. I get the feeling that the shop is trying to create a social environment where people are interacting with one another instead of on their phones (because there's a sign specifically asking customers not to use phones indoors). However, I think this is an issue. Many coffee shop goers go to do work and if they can't access the internet, that's a problem. This is what happened to me - came to do work at around 10am only to discover that I couldn't do any research until 11. I think this issue is further stressed given that 1) it's so close to campus and 2) there's a very well known, very popular shop less than one block over. I write this in hopes that the owners open the internet for as long as the shop is open.

I'm not really sure whether I'd like to give Raging Sage 3 stars or 4. But I do like this place!

name: The Bricks
categories: Bars, Breakfast & Brunch, Restaurants, American (New), Coffee & Tea, Food, Nightlife, Vegetarian
text: My wife and I have visited twice, and another time with friends. While we like the food and beer choices, the service is inexcusably very slow. We visited on a Saturday afternoon around 5:00 and the place was only 1/3 full. Took a while for our server to greet us, arrived just when we were about to get up and leave. Ordered a beer for each of us and waited at least 10 minutes before I finally got up to ask the bartender about our drinks (after watching him not making any drinks for several minutes and serving a few others who just arrived at the bar). I could barely get the words out before he says they'll be right up. I sit back down, and he still doesn't pour them. We were about to leave again when another bartender made eye contact and she poured the drinks and brought them to us. While our waitress was friendly, she should have been checking on our drinks. Same slow experience with the other two visits, this time we are certain we will not be back.

name: Dim Sum House
categories: Shanghainese, Tapas Bars, Cantonese, Seafood, Dim Sum, Chinese, Asian Fusion, Restaurants, Tapas/Small Plates, Szechuan
text:
Jane G's rebranded to Dim Sum House and reopened on Valentine's Day, 2020. This review is a bit belated as I went about 10 days ago, the day after the grand re-opening. 

The interior looks largely the same, while the menu got a total makeover. Gone are the $35 unlimited hot pot and Sichuan dishes, replaced by dim sum. I would have liked to see a few more traditional dishes, but it had most of the major stuff catering to a Rittenhouse crowd. (The prices were in Rittenhouse dollars as well.)

We ordered a few different dishes: hot and sour soup, turnip cake, scallion pancakes, Brussels sprouts (why were these on a dim sum menu?), fried dumplings, crab and pork soup dumplings, and pork belly with mustard greens, which came with a side of rice. 

I knocked off a star because while most dishes were good, the turnip cake was a total miss - quite a bit overdone. I didn't find anything particularly memorable that I would come back for. We did experience quite a few issues with ordering as the kitchen had run out of a few items due to reopening the day before; I completely understand but the issue was that our server (while very nice) was not prepared with this info and had to keep coming back to us to let us know the kitchen was missing something, after we had already ordered. 

Overall, Dim Sum House has a few kinks to work out but it is nice to have them reopen with an Asian option in the neighborhood.

name: Backyard Bowls
categories: Health Markets, Coffee & Tea, Ice Cream & Frozen Yogurt, Restaurants, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Breakfast & Brunch, Food, American (New), Specialty Food
text:
Hands down one of my favorite places to grab quick food in Santa Barbara. Lots of fresh options and a slew of ways to customize your bowl/smoothie so that you get the supreme combination of nutrients and flavors you're looking for. 

Here's the catch: I consistently experience a little bit of spacy-ness from the staff, which usually translates to my order coming out wrong. This wouldn't be a big deal if I could eat granola or honey, but I can't.  So when they overlook my request to swap out granola for chopped almonds, or too quickly douse my bowl in honey before I can yell, "NOOOOOOOO!" I have to be THAT customer who is like, "Uh, I'm afraid I can't eat this."  If this had only happened once, I wouldn't be writing this review.  But it happens on a regular basis, so they get 3/5 stars.  I just hate wasting food. 

All that being said, some top performing menu items - provided you don't mind if they are made to spec or not - are the Popeye smoothie, the Diego bowl and the Island bowl. 

The Diego is a dense, satisfying bowl - particularly in the Large size. The peanut butter sits with you for long stretches of the day, and I usually forget to eat several meals after having one of these.  Not as sweet as the other bowls, but extremely filling. 

The Island is SWEET - even if you forego the honey. Something about the blueberry/banana/strawberry combination is enough to keep you shoveling bites of this bowl down before you can even think to breathe. Doesn't always keep you full for long stretches of time - likely due to the sugar crash you have an hour or so after eating it.  Regardless, if you're looking for a sweet smoothie-esque experience, this is your ticket. 

The Popeye smoothie is everything a green smoothie should be. Nutrient dense, flavorful, refreshing and this crazy vibrant green color - it ups your healthy-eater cred without you even really trying.

name: Nan Zhou Hand Drawn Noodle House
categories: Specialty Food, Noodles, Ethnic Food, Chinese, Comfort Food, Restaurants, Food
text:
Bottom line: No nonsense delicious food at good value. I'd probably eat here once every 1-2 weeks if I lived nearby. 

Food: Had the House special beef noodle soup and opted for the shaved noodles. Was really delicious- the shaved noodles are nice and chewy (QQ), slightly thicker (which I really like), and have a good bite to them. The meat was nice and tender and flavorful and the veggies and broth were also good. Also had the scallion pancake and it was nice and crunchy, flavorful, and the slightly sweet dipping sauce was nice as well.

Value: Shines here- 8-9 bucks for a bowl of noodles and 2.75 for the scallion pancake. Back home in Cupertino, where there is an abundance of delicious Chinese/Taiwanese food, a bowl of noodle soup like that would easily cost me 12-13 bucks and 4-5 for the scallion pancakes. Yay for better values here. Cash only FYI though they have an ATM on site.

Ambiance: Nothing fancy but not a hole in the wall either. Plenty of seating, nice enough tables, non-throwaway chopsticks. 

Service: Fast, efficient, friendly. No frills.

name: The Lark
categories: Nightlife, Bars, Cocktail Bars, Food, American (New), Desserts, Restaurants
text:
After hearing all the buzz, I was very excited to visit Lark. 

We went on a Wednesday night, and the three of us sat outside on the patio. We brought a couple bottles of wine (corkage is $20/bottle). The food is reportedly served family style. We started with the fried, goat cheese-stuffed Castelvetrano olives, and moved on to Caramelized Cauliflower Gratin, Little Gems 'Wedge' salad, Pork Belly Sliders, and Whole Grilled Branzino. For dessert, we had the Chocolate Pot Du Creme and the Meyer Lemon Tart. 

The food was generally OK. The Cauliflower Gratin and Pork Belly Sliders were the best of the dishes we ordered. The portions were fairly small, especially for a family-style approach. I don't think it really is family-style, but that's what they're telling people.

There was something not right about the Lemon Tart. It tasted like liver pate. All three of us tasted this. We pointed it out to our waiter and he said something like "let me check that out" and basically never returned. We were charged for the tart nonetheless. 

I think The Lark has potential, but they're going to have to make some adjustments in order to truly succeed.

name: Villa Rosa
categories: Pizza, Italian, Restaurants
text: What a great surprise I found today in this little Italian restaurant. The casual, bare walls and ripped booth seats had me a bit skeptical, but a bunch of people told me to try it. I'm glad I did. The food is very good, and hot and fresh. The dinners are served with a nice ice cold salad. The baked ziti was hot and cheesey and yummy. I had an order of garlic bread to sop up the fantastic sauce. The tortellini in Alfredo was well done as well as the pizza and strombolis. The laid back atmosphere and personable waiter made for a great night. The topper was the easy on the wallet price!!

name: Mason's
categories: Southern, Restaurants
text: Got to meet Adam Richman here, which automatically gives this place my blessing. It's hard to find a restaurant where the actual food looks as good as the pictures, but this was one of those rare occasions. We sampled 3 of the appetizers: Bone marrow & beef cheek confit, deviled eggs and fried green tomatoes. I would order all of them again, but the deviled eggs were fantastic. Even the pickled okra was good. For my main course, I got the Roast beef and deviled crab sandwich, which was topped with butternut squash slaw, smoked pepper aioli and triple tam brie cheese. Fantastic flavors going on in this sandwich! We finished off the meal with a chef special dessert: GooGoo cluster frozen with liquid nitrogen and served like a small root beer float. Nice! They also have a great bar area.

text: This is my favorite place on DoorDash! Great flavors, amazing sauces and they have been consistent with every order. I also have not had them make mistakes on any order, which I can't say about most restaurants offering delivery. My only complaint is that the baked tortellini dish is small for the price (see pic). I think that a dish that size that doesn't contain any protein (just pasta, cheese and sauce) should be more like $8-10, not $14.  Preferably it would be a dish twice that size and cost $10-12. I'll continue ordering but I'm gonna skip on that dish again unless something changes.

name: Mythos Greek Taverna
categories: Restaurants, Greek
text:
Five stars all the way. 
 I made a reservation on a Wednesday for the Saturday seating. Party of four.
Seated right away with a glass of water. We were told the specials.  I asked if the moussaka was available and she said she made one that day. 
Orders taken in a timely fashion. For wine, the Boutari is probably your best bet.  Only $5.00 more than the house wine. 
Lovely, gigantic portions served up quickly.  Lamb shank was a winner.  My moussaka ($30) was to die for. The pork souvlaki was also tasty and the Pastitsio was huge.  Had to be taken home.  All came with rice, roasted potatoes, buttery green beans and carrots. The Pastitsio came with Greek salad instead of veggies.
They accidentally spilled my mom's tea onto her dinner so they gave her a new order immediately with a new tea.  They apologized all over the place.  We got a huge piece of freshly baked baklava to share and a cup of coffee on the house.  
This lady hosts, cooks and serves.  Her fella also serves and busses.  She told us she is from Cyprus. Shared a story about desserts from her childhood. 
I'm so happy that they don't allow kids after 6pm.  Sorry for all you young families, but I will pay good money not to listen to your kids.

name: Kreis Restaurant
categories: Seafood, Steakhouses, Restaurants
text: Disappointment.   Older host not very friendly.   Salad wedge dressing tasted like sour vinegar - when I asked for blue cheese.   Prime rib undercooked and very tough.  Creamed spinach loaded with nutmeg, interesting but not edible.   Bread in basket with butter was good.   Service was excellent.    No credit offered for food that was not edible.   Will not go back anytime soon.   Not sure why this place is so well known and raved about.  Not impressed.   I know quality meats and this place did not hit the mark.   Sorry for the lousey review, but it's deserved folks.

name: Thunderbird
categories: Southern, Restaurants, Bars, Cocktail Bars, Gastropubs, Nightlife, Beer Bar
text: Another very pretentious hipster bar...I had high hopes as I frequent Fountain Square often, but I was quite let down when I realized what it was. This place is a lot like Bluebeards, except lacking on service and quality of food. Go here if you want slow service, a limited selection of drinks (only our $10 old-timey drinks please!), and massively overpriced food. I had six chicken wings for $8. They were mushy and gross - I'm not exaggerating - they were some of the worst chicken wings I've ever had and at double the price. My friend had a burger that was $12 and was absolutely nothing special. I really see no reason to ever go here unless you want to feel like you're special by overpaying for drinks and food that really aren't very good. TIP: Go to the Brass Ring for better food, service, and value.

name: Chao Vietnamese Street Food
categories: Vietnamese, Restaurants
text: Drove by this place more times than I can remember so my husband suggested we give it a try.  I have to admit that my exposure to Vietnamese Street food is fairly limited so I didn't venture outside my comfort zone all that much on my first viI ordered the Pork Street Tacos which were really good! There is no price on the menu for them which I thought was very odd considering pretty much everything else on the menu had a set price.  I don't particularly like surprises when it comes to menu pricing.  I ordered two and hoped for the best.  For $8.50 they were way too stingy on the ingredients. Two small but tasty flat strips of marinated pork, slaw and a really yummy sauce. I think three would have made a great dinner size but keep it at $8.50 or maybe 3 for $9.  I think that is more than fair. My husband ordered the Steak Rice Bun Noodles ($9.95) and added the egg roll for an add'l ($2.00).  Not worth $12.  Again, pretty skimpy on the flavorful meat and heavy handed on the lettuce and slaw.  Also, the egg roll cut in half on the side of the "salad" was disappointing.  The pricing should have been two egg rolls for something like $2.25.  I think he would have been better off ordering the Steak Rice meal. Perhaps it would have been more filling. He left feeling hungry. The Spring Rolls looked beautiful and were pretty good but it was basically the same meal that my husband ordered just rolled up.  The peanut dipping sauce was yummy.  I would go here again maybe for lunch as those tacos were my favorite of the evening but I don't think they were worth the price.  I did see someone order the Bahn Mi and he too had a very small portion of meat. It was mostly greens.  Didn't look anything like picture #4 posted above.  That one looked staged for advertising purposes.  I can't imagine he didn't hit a drive thru after leaving there.  I will say the staff was awesome! Very friendly and attentive.  Our waitress was respectful of our personal space but she stood so far away it was difficult to hear her quiet voice.  Three stars on flavor, two stars for portion versus cost.

name: Andersen's Danish Bakery & Restaurant
categories: Modern European, Nightlife, Bars, Restaurants, Bakeries, Wine Bars, Food, Scandinavian, Breakfast & Brunch
text:
My girlfriends and I decided to take an overnight vacation from the chaos and noise of Hollywood, and go to Santa Barbara.  Dinner the night we arrived was at a high end place at Stearn's Wharf, and it was very disappointing. I was worried about going to brunch the next morning and having the same kind of experience.

My fears were unnecessary. Andersen's was amazing.  We're not normally the kind of girls that like pink, and lace, and feminine decor, but we LOVED it here. The food was absolutely delicious, and very sensibly priced. We received a plate of pastries and baguette prior to our meals, and the Blackberry Mimosas were superb. This really turned out to be a highlight of our short trip, and we will definitely go back on our next visit to SB!

name: Verducci's Trattoria Pizzeria
categories: Restaurants, Pizza, Seafood, Salad, Italian
text:
Wow what a disappointment.   We had been to ST Pete beach 3 years ago and had read all the rave reviews about the place and ate there twice, even driving an hour back up because of how
Good the food and service was and since we were going to be driving from lake city back to Orlando, we decided to drive back here to have a special meal.   After reading many of the most recent reviews on here and TripAdvisor, I was a little leery because of all the complaints on the food, the service, the lack of caring by staff and mgmt and the length of time for orders or orders being incorrect.  Well all that was true and I'm kicking myself for thinking differently as my dinner was just plain horrible.  

We went at 8:00 tonight and it was half full.  We were seated and drinks were ordered and brought to the table.  Then a different server, Juan was the name on the receipt, came and took our food order.   Of course he didn't write it down or remember it correctly, as you can see where I'm going with this.  We get two pasta dishes, veggie lasagne and gnocchi and 2 Caesar salads.  Pretty simple
Order.   The salads come fairly quickly and only have 2 small croutons on the top.   So it's basically a bowl of romaine with light dressing a sprinkle of cheese and 2 small croutons. Ridiculous considering many of the  complaints have been about "things changing, going downhill, etc ". Then we wait 20-25 min for entrees and they finally come and as Juan is sitting my plate down he asks me if I had the gnocchi or some other lasagne?  Come on bro.  I told him I had the gnocchi and he left and said he would
Be right back.  Well my girl is halfway finished with her dish and mine is still nowhere.   He finally comes back and I ask how long it's going to take because we would like to eat together and he says 5 minutes.  Easily didn't care.  So I told him to cancel it and he said ok.   Of course No manager ever came by, no apology,   All he did to try to recover was ask if I wanted an extra plate to split my girls lasagne after she was half done.  What an idiot.  Didn't offer anything else,  no manager nada.  Then brings it out to go anyways after I told him to cancel it.  I get it that he was trying to be nice but I told
Him I was in a hotel and that's why I said cancel it.  H said oh ok you need a ride?  No dipshit I have a car.   I  wanted dinner on time and correct instead of you blaming the cooks.  That drives me crazy.  You didn't remember the order, you put it in the  computer, you carried the wrong order to the table then blamed it on the cooks to try and save your tip.  Well that didn't work either.  Bad hire, bad training, bad food quality reduction, and clearly no one really caring- just like all the previous bad reviews.   So I'll just add to it

name: Iron Hill Brewery & Restaurant
categories: Breweries, American (New), Restaurants, Food
text: Awesome sauce! This place was fantastic.  The food, the service, the atmosphere, and the beer! And don't fret your non beer loving friends will also find some yummy drinks for themselves as well.  My partner, hates beer, but enjoyed her white sangria.  They have a full bar which is nice for those who don't like beer.  I had a flight and enjoyed the Ziggy Bock and the Clocked out  lager the most. The hipster IPA was also good and so was the red lager. The bock was my favorite but if you like a good IPA I would recommend the Hipster IPA.  Onto the food. I started with the Au gratin onion soup and it was delicious. It had great flavor and wasn't too salty.  My partner had the pretzel sticks and I tried them too.  They were better than the "gourmet" ones at federal hall (hard to beat for those of you who know what I'm talking about.). For my main course I had the  (forge the actual name) roast beef sandwich with Swiss, peppers and horse radish sauce with fries.  Both the sandwich and the fries were really good. My partner had the fish and chips and while she wished the batter had a little more grease to it she said the fish was perfect and would order it again. She loved her fries and I ate her Cole slaw.  Now I have said that moon dog grill/cool dog cafe has the best Cole slaw around.  I have to change that.  The Cole slaw was really good here.  It has a different taste to it but I can't figure out why.   Either way we can't wait to go back here with my brother in a couple of weeks.
