name: Copper Monkey Grill
categories: American (Traditional), Bars, Nightlife, Dive Bars, Restaurants, Food Delivery Services, Food
text:
Great "dive" bar, but it's more of just a great bar with regulars that looks like a dive bar might. Awesome shrimp po boy, the bartender was sweet and funny and you could tell everyone loves her. It was a nice comfortable spot to get some late night drinks and dinner without the headache of the bigger bars in the area. Late 90s/early aughts greatest hits didn't hurt either!

Seems like a great place to catch a football game while still having good service and not having to use your elbows to row your way through a crowd.

name: Shoreline Beach Cafe
categories: Cafes, Burgers, American (Traditional), Tacos, Seafood, Restaurants, Mexican
text:
Weekend covid-19 getaway with the wife. Stumbled upon this beachfront cafe prior to buying a few bottles of wine. Haha gotta buy wine on a full stomach. 

Our waitress Shaine provided us phenomenal welcoming and friendly service. 
We started with mai tai drinks which had a rum forward taste before stirring haha. Can never complain about a liquor taste. We ordered calamari and clam chowder for our appetizers which were great. 

Wifey ordered baha fish tacos and I ordered fish and chips. Just to sum it all up. Everything was light and perfect. The view was fabulous. Definitely a go to when in Santa Barbara.

name: In-N-Out Burger
categories: Restaurants, Burgers, American (New), Fast Food
text:
I have never sat in a drive through for as long as I did today. Having to sit in a line for over 45 minutes for burgers is insane. 
Are the burgers good, yes. Are they worth it, no. I can go to another burger joint with this kind of wait and order multiple times! 
The menu is limited of course which I would assume would make this process faster. But it's not. I will prefer to not go back. 
Now for the food yes it's good. The bread is warm and the patties are thin so get a double double! Animal style makes the burger and fries so much more enjoyable. Especially the fries because they aren't to die for in their own. 
On rainy days kids get a free hot chocolate that was nice. And the people working are always pleasant but I just can't wait that long

name: Mood Cafe
categories: Cafes, Pakistani, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Restaurants, Ice Cream & Frozen Yogurt, Halal, Indian, Coffee & Tea, Food
text:
Paid a visit to Mood Cafe last night. Hassan treated us like family and provided a bevy of samples on the house! He was eager to get us to try new things and demonstrate the range of flavors he could accomplish with just a few ingredients.

Although lassi are dense, the milkshakes, juice, and shaved ice are light. They are good alternatives on hot days as last night was. 

First, we had watermelon juice - fresh and pulpy. Next we sampled a vanilla and date milkshake which was delicious. The chewy dates at the bottom of the shake reminded me of bubble tea. He also served us a couple of variants of shaved ice which were not unlike parfait; there was cut fruit at the bottom of the cup along with crushed ice topped with light syrups. The syrup flavors were rose and sandalwood! He also provided a similar shaved ice with pineapple. 

NOTE: For all you vegans out there, Mood Cafe has stocked up on almond, soy, and coconut milk. Seems like most items are available in vegan form. 

You win, Hassan. Five stars. My stomach can't take any more.

name: Sangiovese Ristorante
categories: Italian, Restaurants
text: My fianc and I were at Sangiovese on Valentines Day. We were in a small room off the main dining room. It was intimate and cute and I liked the ambiance a lot. Our server was very bubbly. She was transparent about the wait for our food saying they'd taken too many carry out orders. We were there about an hour and 45 minutes. We were getting our waters filled by various people so, so often. Like 3/4 full and above. I was pleasantly surprised to see they'd continued their devour menu and that was a really great value. The Caesar salad was flavorful and well dressed. The mushroom pesto pasta was pretty good, just need to be down for something suuper earthy. My fianc was pleased with his entree. I wasn't wowed by my cocktail or the desert. I'd give em another shot on a less busy night.

text: Love this little cafe at the end of the trail, as it's name notes.  Great coffee.  Delicious pastries and treats.  And friendly service.  They have done a nice job making this old train station into a cozy little place to take a break, read a book or meet with a friend for a coffee.  Love it.  Highly recommended.

name: Zim Zari
categories: Cocktail Bars, Restaurants, Bars, American (New), Food, Nightlife, Mexican, Burgers
text:
Went there for lunch the other day (Friday) It was busy so we sat at a tall table in the bar.  The iced tea tasted fresh brewed from real tea bags and not the powdered stuff.  I asked for it with extra lime and was actually given LIME (and extra slices in a small dish on the side) not lemon.  In most places, requesting lime instead of lemon seems to stymie most servers.  Major brownie points.

My only complaint is about the chips and salsa.  Granted, it's complimentary but the chips were thin and flavorless.  The salsa was ok.  I ordered the ahi tacos.  I have to say they were amazing.  The ahi was fresh and well-seasoned.  My friend ordered the upside down nachos.  The portion was generous, meriting a to-go box.  

Our server was friendly but not overbearing.  Drink refills were offered quickly.  Our food arrived within 10 minutes of ordering.  We sat for awhile and chatted but were not made to feel like we were taking up space.  Being an ex-server I know how irritating  it is when diners "campout" at a table because in places like this, faster table turnovers equal more tips.  That was appreciated and our server was generously  compensated.  Will definitely recommend.

name: Global Foods Market
categories: Coffee & Tea, Food, Grocery, International Grocery, Restaurants, Ethnic Food, Specialty Food
text:
Great place to go if you're looking for international and unique ingredients! If Global Foods doesn't have it, you don't need it!

For Christmas my mom always does the traditional meal - turkey/ham/potatoes/green beans/corn/salad/rolls/etc. - but every year since I can remember she always does an ethnic side dish. We've had Mexican, Filipino, Greek, Thai, Puerto Rican, Ethiopian, Italian, Venezuelan, Indian, Cuban, etc. and recently within the last few years we've relied on Global Foods for the unique spices or ingredients those dishes call for. Luckily for us Global usually carries a couple varieties of said ingredient/spice so we have options to chose from!

Not only do they have a great variety of fresh, frozen & packaged items, but the aisles (outside of perishable items) are organized by country which makes it so much easier to find what you need! But if you still can't find an item, ask one of the friendly associates to help you!

So next time you're creating a unique dish or have a craving for something specific, go to Global Foods!

Only downfall is their parking lot - it's always busy and sometimes hard to find a spot! But that speaks to how wonderful it is inside :)

name: The Wild Cow
categories: American (New), Vegan, Restaurants, Vegetarian
text:
Another fantastic VEGAN spot in Nashville!  I brought a carnivore here, and even he was blown away.  We both had the French Dip and it was fantastic (I didn't want to have food envy)!  As an appetizer, we had the vegan queso, which was also great.  This is the kind of spot I wish I had back home close to me, as I would definitely be a regular.  I think I'm starting to understand why Johhny T. left Miami for Nashville.  Its because of all the great food.  

We came in for a late lunch, and the place wasn't busy at all.  We had great service from our waiter, who was a transplant from S. Florida.  

Overall amazing food and service, great concept and would definitely go back when I am in the area.

name: Gulf Bistro
categories: French, Seafood, Diners, Restaurants
text: My expectations were high after reading some good reviews online. My wife and I got dressed up to have a nice dinner at a French restaurant so we were ready to be wowed. As we arrived, the decor evoked a nice french atmosphere but not in an overpowering or cheesy manner. We even heard another couple exclaim how good their meal was to the server as they left, right after we sat down. The restaurant filled to about half capacity as our meal progressed. Our meal started well; the lobster bisque starter was very good but that was the high point. I followed the bisque with escargot, but it was pretty bland (as well as runny) and my wife was not enamored with the cheese on the onion soup. For our entrees, shrimp/scallops (me) and grouper, but neither were that flavorful.  We opted out of dessert at that point. Perhaps our experience was not typical, given some of the other indications about this restaurant, but we will not be back.

text:

I stepped in to get a breakfast sandwich to go while a friend was in line at a specialty meat shop across the street.  I got egg and cheese on an everything bagel. I wanted to punch my mom's glasses off their faces.  I got out as soon as I could.

name: Apricot Stone
categories: Food, Restaurants, Armenian, Middle Eastern, Mediterranean
text:
In the constant search for that "perfect dish" with the freshest ingredients being used, it has been a challenge well worth experiencing. Exploring almost all of Philadelphia, this beautiful city, along with the outskirts for that one perfect Mediterranean/Middle Eastern dish has been an adventure. Mind you this hasn't been easy , some have also been costly in our expedition. With the establishments I (we) have been to in and around the city, our taste buds have experienced the great, down to the sub par. 

This has all come to fruition my friends with Apricot Stone being in Northern Liberties. I want to thank Sari, my partner in crime in joining me on this savory journey. 

Apricot Stone is literally a "hidden gem" located in Northern Liberties of all places. Not that I have anything against No. Libs. mind you. We came here one night for dinner and we immediately knew we had to come back .  

If you decide to come here for dinner you will be amazed, or if you decide on brunch you'll be overwhelmed by it. It is pretty safe to say you'd be in an euphoric bliss in which ever route you decide on.  Enough of the explaining, let me show you what I enjoyed with dinner along with brunch.  I also want to point out their hummus is the best I have ever tasted, Zahav is a close second in my opinion.  

Dinner: 
Kebab Tasting plate~ I highly recommend if you were to go for dinner. This is where you choose 3 items along with a dip to enjoy and a salad. The dish I had prepared consisted of : Chicken shawarma, falafel, lamb kebab were my main. My dip and salad were an eggplant salsa to go with an Israeli salad that which consisted of tomatoes and cucumbers in a homemade dressing. This is not a small plate by the way, our dishes were over flowing, with a ridiculous cost of $15.00. No that is not a typo, for $15 dollars you'll be enjoying an amazing dinner. 

Now onto Sunday brunch where we  could hardly contain ourselves, knowing what is ahead of us.  Sunday Funday  is upon us, and why not share our enjoyment with another Yelper that we all know and love with Mariella S. Pop that bottle, bring on the mimosas because this will definitely put you at full tilt. My brunch, which was another over flowing dish by the way. This is also a considered a "Chefs tasting menu" for a whopping $20.00 dollars. Shhhh I know, now please read on. 
 
*Mamounia~ This is a very sweet dish that is a cream of wheat, made with pistachio with their homemade cheese. A little too sweet for me, but still very good. 
*Zakhtar bread~ This is a flatbread that has been covered with their herbs and spices that has a crunchy flavorful taste to it .   
*Khachapri~ This is a dish that is bad ass, that needs to be ordered. It is their own homemade dough shaped like a boat stuffed with cheese that has been baked with an egg sunny side up over top. Bruh.. UHHH-maz-ING, this is what I consider winning all day.
*Falafel salad~ One larger than life falafel over a bed of lettuce mixed with cucumbers and tomatoes. 
*Apricot Crumb Cake~ Like we could eat any more , they push it to the limit with this. An apricot jam filled crumb cake that will have you screaming obscenities, that's how good it is.  

The space may not be big, but what they do is utilize the space they do have. Almost to the point where it would feel like you are sitting at home.  A  comforting atmosphere with also outside seating if you would like to dine alfresco. 

I also want to thank Susan G.(former Yelper) for pointing me in the direction of  this phenomenal restaurant.  Everyone should find the time , and simply take in one of or better yet all of their amazing dishes. I still want to try their well known Baklava with walnuts , the last 2 times I (we) have been in there, they have been sold out.  

I plan on coming back to this gem of all gems, so get ready Mrs. Fimy. Also if you could put aside a piece of the baklava I would greatly appreciate it, I'll even call ahead of time.

name: Coquette
categories: Restaurants, French, American (New)
text: Ah, Coquette. The most special meal of our visit to NOLA. Warm, intimate, romantic, unpretentious and oh so delicious. Service was great. They were thoughtful enough to add a candle to my GF's dessert because my online reservation mentioned we were coming for her birthday. The menu requires some explaining if you're not a foodie but the server was more than familiar with each item and did a great job helping us decide between all the yummy options. My advice is save up and order from each category- sharings, small plates, entrees, dessert- because each is something fantastic to behold and to savor. If you have the time, stroll that area along Magazine St before or after dinner, it's very cool as well.

name: La Estrella Bakery
categories: Restaurants, Bakeries, Food
text: So I'm traveling through Tucson this week and I had to find myself a local bakery that specialized in Hispanic type pastries. I got two or three things including a couple of glazed donuts which were really good. The best thing that I got there was the fresh flour tortillas. I saw that they were selling them on the counter and so I asked The very nice lady behind the counter for a pack of fresh ones. She actually went into the back and grabbed a pack that were so fresh they were really hot. I am a huge fan of good flour tortillas especially when they're made right and they're fresh. These are some of the best I have ever had and I hope someday to come back to Tucson and experience more of these. Even if you have to drive from the other side of town they are worth it. Thank you very much to the friendly woman behind the counter because you started my day off with a smile and a wonderful breakfast!

text: Gave it 4 star because it is new and working through some kinks and I am happy to have a new restaurant in the hood. Stuffed risotto balls needed less risotto more mozzarella but we liked the fried outside consistence. The pizza had a great yummy thin crust but was a little salty for our taste (we had the meat lovers and I think maybe the meat was what was so salty). Some additional salad/ vegetable options would be nice to add to the menu but I think its still working on a limited menu.  Overall an okay first experience but we will definitely be back to try more!

name: The Urban Stillhouse
categories: Nightlife, Food, Distilleries, Restaurants, Bars, American (New), Whiskey Bars
text: We had an awesome time here! The vibe is very laid back yet upscale with leather couches all around. Our group ended up being about 12 people so we rented out a room upstairs. The place was extremely accommodating and gave us a lot of attention! We were able to stream our own music in the room and we had our own little dance parry! The food was great - I especially enjoyed the short ribs, lamb chops AND don't forget the goat cheese and potato gratin - YUMMM... I don't drink a lot of Bourbon but asked that they make me a drink that was fresh and citrusy and it was DEFINITELY awesome! The cocktails were off the chain! I don't have any pictures of the food but we had an amazing night and will definitely be back.

name: BurgerBarr
categories: Burgers, American (Traditional), American (New), Restaurants
text: Folks tend to over sale or exaggerate the details of their experience in a lot of places. So I won't say something crazy like, these are the best burgers in jersey. I can't say that because I live in Philadelphia and feel like these are the best burgers in the tri-state area. Whichever trio of states you want to use, these burgers are the best in that group. Don't mind driving the hour and change because the burgers are that good. The menu offers many options to customize your version of the perfect burger. Almost too many options, but let your creativity go wild. All the options are promising(except adding an egg. I mean, do you). Besides excellent burgers, spectacular fries, the service is tremendous. Just a warm friendly group of people. It's a no frills type of spot, but a top notch experience every time.

text:
This place has very unique special rolls. Met up with a friend as we were feeling sushi and looked ahead of time at the menu and had a rough time choosing between several special rolls. Went w the Red Dragon, Shrimp on Fire, Bugz, Spicy Tuna and the Torch Peno. The Red Dragon was my favorite along with the Bugz. Service was great and very friendly. The food came out in a timely manner and we ate till we were more than full. 

If you're looking for a sushi spot that's a bit different and interesting, def come try this spot out. Excited to go again sometime soon to try out other rolls we didn't get on this past trip.

name: Terakawa Ramen
categories: Japanese, Ramen, Ethnic Food, Restaurants, Local Flavor, Food, Specialty Food
text:
the most consistent and best tasting ramen in philly. 

formerly ramen boy, this place has matured significantly and the food offerings are much better after they re-branded as terakawa (a welcome import from NY) and switched chefs. 

the broth for the ramen is really consistent (many other places in philly are good some days, and sub-par on other days) and offers a very balanced taste - not too overly seasoned but very flavorful. definitely get the terakawa noodles in everything, including the tan tan noodles which normally come with another type of noodle (the terakawa noodles are the best). 

a very nicely done decor but not a lot of fluff (which is good - nom nom is overly "fast food" like with a mcdonalds feel, and hiro is a direct ripoff of this place that doesn't quite measure up). 

i would recommend the octopus balls, the pork buns, and the gyoza - all very well done and reasonably priced. i especially like the fact that you can get many appetizer pairings with ramen as a lunch special - very convenient.

name: Bangkok Kitchen Thai Restaurant
categories: Thai, Restaurants, Wine Bars, Bars, Cocktail Bars, Nightlife
text:
The BEST Thai you'll find in Avon. Cozy aesthetic, amazing food, and wonderful service. I love going to Bangkok Kitchen whenever I am in town. My parents visit 1-2 times/week it's that good!

My mom and I split a variety of dishes during our most recent visit. Golden tofu, Khao Soi with shrimp (the special of the day), and crab fried rice. We definitely had leftovers, but felt like trying a little bit of this and a little bit of that :) I would recommend all three items, especially the Khao Soi soup. It was the perfect blend of sweet (from the coconut milk broth), salty, and crunchy. The noodles were super tasty.

PROS:
Cute interior. They always have nice, seasonal touches. See photos for Easter themed decor.

Big portions! A lot of bang for your buck.

Great service. I've never been disappointed with the wait staff or the wait time.

Delicious!

Delivery available.

Clean bathrooms.



CONS:
Can't think of anything!

name: Hattie Bs Hot Chicken - Nashville
categories: American (Traditional), Chicken Shop, Southern, Restaurants, Chicken Wings, American (New), Soul Food
text:
When you see the line that wraps around this place you might tend to think that it may not be worth the wait.  You'd be wrong.  I'm not a big fried chicken person but this by far is the best ever.  Very crispy outside and juicy and tender inside.  I got the DAMN HOT and it was.  The dry rub/seasoning on the top got stuck underneath my nails and it was pretty damn hot.  My guy got the medium and said it was a little spicy for him but that it was the best chicken ever.  He loves fried chicken and we try places all over the country when we travel.

You gotta try this place, they don't disappoint.  Well worth the wait!!!  We will be back!

text:
This place is great! Had heard many people talking about it, and finally ate there yesterday for the first time. Definitely one of the top BBQ spots in STL. 

I got the pulled chicken plate with the mac n cheese and fries. It was phenomenal and very fair price, especially for how much food you get. My wife got the pulled pork sandwich and loved it as well. Can't wait to go back again soon!

name: The Crossing
categories: French, Restaurants, American (New), Italian
text:
We had dinner here as part of restaurant week last night and while the food wasn't bad, it wasn't amazing either. Nice ambiance & great service though. Good date spot!

I started off with the Rigatoni, which was pretty good, but tasted like something I could easily make at home. For the entree, I went with the Tilapia, which was good for a tilapia but the dish did not leave me wanting more. It came with a carrot puree which was really good though...probably my favorite part of the dish. For dessert, I went with the Chocolate Torte, which again, was good, but tasted like any other warm brownie + ice cream combination I've ever had.

Overall, I really can't complain since the RW dinner priced at $25 really is a great deal. But I don't think I'd come here to pay regular prices. The meal was good, but forgettable, although I do have to say that blue cheese souffle was pretty tasty!

name: Dough Nation
categories: Cafes, Bakeries, Ice Cream & Frozen Yogurt, Restaurants, Food, Desserts
text: Dough Nation is an iconic staple of Downtown Tampa. The decor there is very homey and nice, and the staff are always helpful and very nice. At Dough Nation, they offer ice cream and egg-free cookie dough. This means that, yes, you can eat the cookie dough without having to worry about getting sick. My personal flavor is Double Chocolate Oreo. They offer many flavors like Chocolate Chip, Toasted S'more, Sweet and Salty, Red Velvet, and M&M. You could eat the cookie dough, or even take it home and bake it at 350 degrees in any conventional oven to make delicious cookies. Another great thing, besides the cookie dough, is that all the staff are homeless people going through culinary school at Metropolitan Ministries, as well as the proceeds go to Metropolitan Ministries. This means that not only do you get to eat delicious guilt-free cookie dough, you are also giving back to the community. The feeling of giving back is great; and it's not just the cookie dough sitting in your stomach.

name: Mama Thai
categories: Thai, Restaurants
text:
Mama Thai is great. As soon as you walk through the door you are greeted warmly by the owners or staff. I go here often with my coworkers for lunch. The food is fresh and comes out pretty fast. 

If your lucky Mama will be walking around talking to everyone at their tables. Fun fact: she opened the first Thai Restaurant in New Orleans, which my mom frequented often back then.  

They have gluten free items on the menu marked clearly for you to see and can modify some dishes to accommodate to gluten-free, just ask and they will let you know. I really love that when ordering and inquiring about the menu and modifications they seem very knowledgeable and don't make you feel like a huge pain in the @ss. 

They have rice and glass noodles which are gluten free and if your going the low carb route you can't lose with their curry! Ask for a extra veggies to bulk it up if your not eating rice because you'll want to eat up all of the yummy sauce! 

I was in the mood for Pad Thai and asked if they could make it gluten free. While my dish was yummy and I very much enjoyed it, the modification left it not tasting like Pad Thai, it was missing the sweetness from the tamarind. That being said it was still a delicious meal and left quite satisfied. 

I really have no complaints when I eat here. The staff is very attentive and willing to make sure you have a wonderful time. Check them out and tell them Whitney @ Alligator Pear sent you!

name: Grace Bistro
categories: Restaurants, Chinese, Food, Bubble Tea
text:
We gave up on Wu's a long while ago after their quality hit the tubes.

We were excited to see the location "reborn" as Grace Bistro, with new blood and new management. We gave them a shot the other night. Unfortunately, we ended up disappointed.

The young man who took my order over the phone did a fine job. We picked up, and the food was ready on-time. That's in their favor. First warning sign was a Chinese restaurant that had run out of chopsticks. Then, the food.

We had mainstays of any Chinese menu - sweet & sour chicken, General Tso's chicken, egg rolls, and a Chinese Pizza/Scallion Pancake. The disappointment got underway quickly.

The Sweet & Sour didn't come with enough sauce. The General Tso was "meh", and the scallion pancake was downright terrible.

We usually order from Mulan, over on Evesboro-Medford Rd, who delivers in a short time, and is excellent quality as well as very tasty, two qualities that Grace can't match up on. Hopefully they improve, but as of today, I wouldn't return.

name: Jeannine's Bakery & Restaurant
categories: American (Traditional), Coffee & Tea, Breakfast & Brunch, Food, Bakeries, Restaurants
text:
Great place for breakfast!  Come early to beat the crowd and find street parking.  

Didn't realize that we're supposed to get a table # before we order, but it wasn't a big deal.  Good amounts of seats both inside and out.  

I ordered the Homemade Granola with vanilla yogurt and berries and my husband had the French Toast breakfast with over easy eggs and sausage.  

The yogurt was good with their granola, but I couldn't believe at how much granola they give you!  It was a whole bowl of it.  One negative thing was that this little tiny bug crawled out of it, but since it was so small, I just killed it and continued eating vs making a scene about it.  It was those little bugs that sometimes you'll see in grains.

The French toast was good, but portions were smaller than expected.  Sausage was good and not greasy like most breakfast joints.  Coffee is from Peet's.

Prices are reasonable.  The staff are friendly.  Would go back if I'm in the area.

name: King Dough Indy
categories: Restaurants, Pizza, Chicken Wings, Burgers
text:
Great food, prompt and friendly service, and delicious Neapolitan style pizza. There's a ton of character and good food to be had here, whether it's for its open kitchen/dining interior, its amusing graffiti in the bathrooms (which are spotless), or it's unique menu; it's certainly worth a trip to check it out.

There isn't really parking to be had off the street, so start looking to park before you arrive and walk in. It's also not a very large place but with big open ceilings, and because the space is totally open concept between the kitchen and the full dining area it can get moderately loud. They are very strict on no substitutions or alterations to anything on the menu. I like that since it makes wait times lower and keeps confusion and incorrect orders to a minimum, but if like me you don't like spicy food, you can't "leave something off".  You can pay for a build-your-own to get whatever you want, of course. 

Speaking of spiciness, nothing on the menu really indicates how hot something will be, and since you can't leave it off you really need to ask about that to your server.

name: Irene's
categories: Italian, Restaurants
text:
Upon entering Irene's, a French Quarter based Italian restaurant, three or four well dressed servers greeted us. We felt very welcome and at ease. Irene DiPietro herself was walking through each dining room. Irene's is only open for dinner so we showed up for an early dinner because we didn't want to wait in a line. Upon our exit there were 10 people (locals and tourists) waiting outside the restaurant. If you do not have to wait more than 30 minutes, Irene's is worth the trip.

Irene's has multiple dining rooms. The tables are packed quite tightly together and I could hear our neighbor's conversations. My dining companion asked for her seat to be adjusted because it was wobbling and another tables server seemed a bit sassy, but was willing to help.

The striped wall paper, books, gold framed paintings and lighting was cozy.

Complimentary mozzarella, tomato and basil bruschetta

I started my meal with a caprese salad with well seasoned tomatoes, mozzarella, arugula, pumpkin seeds and onions $5.50.


My friend had the ricotta and spinach raviolis with red sauce and seemed quite pleased with her choice $7.50.

I had a soft shell crab meuniere appetizer special as my main. It was lightly fried, the crab meat was juicy and served with slivered almonds, brown butter and lemon.

We shared the Bananas Foster Bread pudding, suggested by our enthusiastic, New Orleans born and raised waitress, it was unbelievable. The bread pudding was served with warmed bananas and rum caramel sauce, vanilla ice cream and whipped cream.

name: Bakersfield
categories: Restaurants, Sandwiches, Bars, Nightlife, Tex-Mex, Tacos, Mexican
text: My husband and I was in Nashville for the CMA Fest this year and was looking for good food at local places. This place has good reviews so we checked it out. We ordered the trio and a couple tacos each. Everything was delicious. The food came back so fast! The flavor was awesome and the ingredients tasted so fresh! We liked it so much we came back again our last night and got the trio again (which the guacamole and salsas are so good and the chips are perfectly cooked/seasoned) and a couple different tacos. All of the tacos we tried were so delicious. I tried the fish, shrimp, corn/veggie and bistec tacos. My husband ordered the bistec and pork tacos both times. The drinks were very good too. I got the seasonal margarita which was strawberry. Would highly recommend Bakersfield. I will be going again when I go back to Nashville!

name: Fat Salmon
categories: Restaurants, Sushi Bars, Japanese
text:
I couldn't decide between giving this place 3 or 4 stars, but I settled on 4 because I would definitely go back.

We ordered the agedashi tofu, shrimp tempura tofu, smoked salmon, fluke, and yellowtail nigiri, their Rock N Roll special roll, and their Shochu samplers.

I'll start with the decor. It's very ultra white, space age modern looking. Interesting take on decor for a sushi restaurant, of which I'm not sure if I am a fan but I can't say I hate it, either.

Now for the food. The agedashi tofu was nothing special, i.e. don't bother ordering this dish. The shrimp tempura udon was pretty good, but not fantastic. I did like how they served the 2 shrimp tempura on the side so that it doesn't get too soggy in the broth. It also came with a zucchini tempura fritter.

The nigiri was pretty much to my expectation, although they did something weird to the smoked salmon and yellowtail that made it look like the texture of cube steak. It was very odd and I assume its purpose is to tenderize the fish. The Rock N Roll was a commitment. Each piece, or roll, was pretty thick and stuffed with both salmon and tuna, then topped with "crunchy" topping and a sweet eel sauce. The waitress explained that it is called eel sauce because they mix in powdered eel. I have no idea what that is.

In summary, they have a variety of sushi options, to the point where their menu is overwhelming, as well as many non-sushi options. They also seemed to have a pretty good sake selection. Their service is fine- nothing remarkable, though. I would definitely recommend this place if you are looking for a nice, reasonably priced sushi joint that serves alcohol.

name: Cacia's Bakery
categories: Delis, Sandwiches, Food, Pizza, Restaurants, Bakeries
text: I was in the mood for an above average, mom and pop, Italian deli hoagie. And man did Cascia's deliver. Great bread, crunchy outside but soft chew inside. The bread makes or breaks a sandwich and the bread here is outstanding.  The meats and cheese are all fresh sliced and piled high. The peppers were fresh and full of flavor. This is just an honestly great hoagie. Fresh mozzarella on the second sub we ordered. Nice assortment of dessert, bread, and frozen meals to go. Found my new deli. I'll be back asap.

name: Small Mart
categories: Food, Grocery, Shopping, Bagels, Indian, Asian Fusion, Restaurants, Vegetarian
text:
This is my favorite little food spot by the Marigny/Bywater. Lots of great vegan and pescatarian options to be had. The bagels are from H&H in New York, so I'm always pleased by that.  (Although they could work on smearing the whole bagel with cream cheese evenly, but I'm from New York, what can I say) 
Their Indian food is my favorite. The samosas and chaat bowl are my go tos but the bagels and bagel sandwiches are a close second!

Covid note: all takeout, very safe, masks required, staff all wearing masks

name: Sushi On Oracle
categories: Sushi Bars, Japanese, Restaurants
text:
Recommended by Yelpers, I found myself here on a weeknight... and the place was packed!  I was happy to find a place at the bar with my husband. 

 Miso soup and edamame were quickly served after we received drinks.  I ordered seaweed salad - and it's a big, delicious salad!  The sushi was also great - simple, well prepared, delicious.  I'm eager to try more on the menu.

I have to say, I can't wait to come back.  The atmosphere is very inviting and the service was excellent.  See you soon, on Oracle!

name: Bern's Steak House
categories: Arts & Entertainment, Steakhouses, Restaurants
text:
TIP:  Consider making your reservation for 5PM, right when they open.  In case you hadn't noticed, this place is VERY popular and is packed every night of the week.  By 6PM you will see a line of people waiting for their tables and that line gets longer and longer as the night goes on.  

We had a 5PM reservation and were sat immediately.  No wait, no fuss.  
I saw others standing in the waiting area well over an hour for their table and they looked miserable!  

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What else is there to say that hasn't already been said?  They place is great. Food is top notch, prices are reasonable, overall dining experience is very unique. 

-Oysters on half shell were fresh and delicious
-Porterhouse Steak was cooked perfectly.
-Sides (baked potato, salad, etc.) were very small portions but given they are included rather than a la carte, one can't complain
-Do the tour, it's part of the experience
-Deserts were AWESOME! - I think we ordered almost every desert on the menu to share with our group and nobody had any complaints
-Port Sampler - If you like Port as an after dinner drink, they have a nice Sampler which comes with a 10 year, 20 year, 30 year and 40 year old samples of ports.

name: Gianni's NY Pizza
categories: Restaurants, Pizza, Chicken Wings, Italian, Sandwiches
text: People rave about this place, but frankly I don't get it. The food is okay but very overpriced for what you get. Tonight I got chicken parm with spaghetti. It was served in an aluminum disposable pan and I was provided with plastic utensils. I could almost count the few strands of spaghetti in the pan with the chicken. The sauce was very bland. For the premium price I expect at least a real plate and metal silverware, which is standard at other such restaurants. Since I know of at least two other local places serving the same fare (and better tasting) for less, I don't plan to return. Still, I feel I'm almost alone according to the reviews, but the five other people with me were also expecting better. I guess the cook who left to start his own restaurant took all the good recipes and silverware with him because his place is great!

name: Arnold's Country Kitchen
categories: Comfort Food, Southern, Desserts, Food, Restaurants
text: After weeks of healthy clean eating, I was craving some turnip greens, mac n cheese (meat and 3) type meal. I have lived in Nashville all my life but had never eaten at Arnold's because I have been disappointed by most "meat and threes". But today I wanted to fulfill that craving. I was one of those customers that arrived 2 minutes before closing. Well, I will have to say Arnold's didn't disappoint. I had roast beef, turnip greens, mac n cheese and cornbread. All was delicious and seasoned to perfection. I won't be eating this type food regularly, but when I have a craving for some good ole home cooking, Arnold's will be at the top of the list.

name: Rolf and Daughters
categories: Italian, American (New), Restaurants, Mediterranean
text: Every time I come to Nashville I make it a point to get dinner here.  Their menu changes slightly with the season but when I was there I had a steak tartar and a tomato/mozzarella appetizer that were unbelievably flavorful.  They didn't use a lot of ingredients because each one was so fresh that you wanted them all to be highlighted.  I've had their pastas both times I went (including the squid) and both were fantastic.  I highly recommend this place.  You can tell they care about the quality of their dishes - a gem!

name: Mr. Dunderbak's
categories: Beer, Wine & Spirits, Food, Pubs, German, American (Traditional), Restaurants, Bars, Nightlife
text:
We came for lunch on a Sat afternoon. This is a
Bergarten or drinking establishment that serves good german food. The furniture is either wooden chairs and small tables or picnic tables. The picnic tables are shared tables if you have a small party.
It is not very comfortable seating. The restaurant is 
nicely decorated in an authentic german theme.
There are german specialty packaged foods and beer steins available for purchase.
The food was good. I had a german triple decker
 sandwich similar to a Rueben. My wife had a sauerbraten sandwich with gravy. Both came with chips and a pickle. The menu has  many other sandwiches as well as other items
such as schnitzels, sausages, pork loin and pirogies. They have a very large beer selection consisting  of both on tap and bottle.

name: Pickles & Swiss
categories: Delis, Gluten-Free, Fast Food, Salad, Sandwiches, Restaurants
text: This is honestly the best sandwich place I've ever been to. A man sitting outside even told us that we were making the right decision because "it's the best lunch place in Santa Barbara" and I agree! The pricing was great for the quantity you get and the quality of the meats and toppings were on point. The brie and prosciutto melted in my mouth and the jam flavor complimented them perfectly. This place is doing business right and I hope they keep up the good work.

name: Han's Chimaek
categories: Korean, Chicken Wings, Nightlife, Bars, Beer Bar, Restaurants, Chicken Shop
text: Wow, does this place have a lot of hype and buzz. It's great! I normally don't go somewhere just for their wings, but this was one spot I had to check out before I left town. I'm so glad I did. When you walk in, you quickly notice that you're in a narrow spot. You feel almost on stage, because there are tables on both sides of the center walkway up to the counter. Almost seems like the people on the side are eagerly anticipating what you're going to order...what's it going to be today? Well, let me give you a recommendation: try the Yangnyum wings, either bone-in or boneless. You will not be disappointed. It's a mixture of sweet and spicy, with small peanuts on top. You don't even need to get rice that normally comes with the wings. Let the wings speak for themselves, and if spicy stuff gives you fits, make sure you have some water or milk handy. You should be alright though. Enjoy- this place CERTAINLY lived up to the hype and I just wish I lived here so I could come all the time!

categories: Hot Dogs, Vegetarian, Burgers, Restaurants, Food Stands, Sandwiches
text: Chicago Paulie's is the real deal, old neighborhood, Chicago Hot dog and beef stand. It looks live a dive, but it will not disappoint. The Chicago dog is real Vienna beef. The bun, steamed, poppie seed, with all the right fixings.  It was perfection! But as good as the hot dog was the beef was AMAZING. It's hard to find good bread in Florida. This was excellent. The beef cut thin. The au juice was seasoned so good I wanted to drink it.  Best of all, the hospitality of Paulie, and the prices. I'll be back again and again. Highly recommend to all Chicagoans and everyone else.

text: The west side of Indy is under rated when it comes to restaurants. There are some hidden gems and Yannis Golden Gyros is one of them. With a lunch like that you almost don't mind going back to work. :)

name: Uncorked Wine Tasting and Kitchen
categories: Nightlife, Wine Bars, Bars, American (Traditional), Tapas/Small Plates, Tapas Bars, Food, Arts & Entertainment, Wine Tasting Room, Wineries, American (New), Restaurants
text:
Uncorked is such a fantastic addition to Santa Barbara. All the food I've eaten there has been delicious. They have a happy hour taco special which is very reasonable and extremely high quality. Now that we are sheltering in place, I'm really enjoying their take home meals. They are great value because you get so much food! And it's so good! 

I like the vibe in the place, it's relaxed and fun. Being able to select from different wines makes it more like an outing and it's nice to be able to taste various wines and then choose to have a full glass of something.

I'm so grateful for them now during shelter in place, I was able to get some much needed groceries from them - they are doing a service to the community.

name: Top Out Cafe
categories: Coffee & Tea, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Restaurants, Food
text: I checked out the Top Out Cafe ahead of a climb. Located on the upper level, it overlooks the majority of the gym. There's long tables that invite you to plug in if you have a computer, high top tables by the bar and even a couch in front of a large television. The cafe caters to lighter, healthier fare and even has beer on tap. I'm a sucker for a fancy grilled cheese - and I was 100% happy with the gourmet grilled cheese. The sandwich is the perfect size with fresh capicola, a srirachi aioli, and havarti cheese make an explosion of flavor in your mouth. The sandwich is served with a handful of sweet and spicy kettle chips. You can select from something on tap (HINT: if you plan on having alcohol, you won't be able to climb - so plan accordingly), a variety of canned La Croix, smoothies, coffee or tap water.

name: Naked Farmer
categories: American (New), Juice Bars & Smoothies, Food, Restaurants, Desserts, American (Traditional), Coffee & Tea
text:
Great food but need to develop a better process for prepping online orders. Every time I go in there's about 5 online orders they work before serving those that are waiting.  Assign a worker to prepping online orders and another to in person so the in person folks aren't waiting while you fill fill the online orders.  

Also suggest requiring orders of 10 or more to be online.  At least twice I've been waiting in line and people in front of me have a list of 10, yes 10, or more orders.  This creates a ridiculous bottle neck.  The last time I was waiting in line and this occurred, I spotted at least 5 people open the door and walk right out.  That's lost revenue that could have been earned if you politely suggest the person order their 10 bowls online. I'm not suggesting you deny making them the order in person, rather making the suggestion after you've completed the order so they don't do it again.  The times I've been in it's been the same person with the order of 10 or more.

Like I said great food, you just need to streamline your processes.

name: Urban Fresh
categories: Vegan, Live/Raw Food, Food, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch
text: I work downtown and I've explored a lot of restaurants in the area.  I went here originally just because it's close and the service is friendly, but recently started eating vegan.  It just so happens this place is really special whether you are vegan or not.  You can eat healthy food that also tastes terrific. The special today was shepherd's pie with a side of sauted veggies.  Filling, as good as the meat version, and healthy to boot. Smoothies are fabulous.  Regular items like the wraps can be made with kale leaves instead of a tortilla.  You can get terrific tea or a young coconut to drink, soups, salads, etc.  Unlike some vegan places where the staff seems stoned or lethargic or disorganized, these people are friendly and energetic and efficient.  Can't say enough good stuff about Urban Fresh and am grateful I happen to work down the street from what is (for me) the perfect lunch spot.

name: Mios Grill & Cafe
categories: Beer Bar, Vegetarian, Greek, Bars, Mediterranean, Turkish, American (Traditional), American (New), Nightlife, Restaurants
text:
I enjoyed my visit last time so much I brought some friends from out of town to come try it out. The service persons remembered my SO and I from our last visit. We didn't mention anything about it. I was quite surprised!

Baba ganoush: It tasted less smoked compared to last time but it was just as good!
Chicken Gyro Platter: This was really satisfying 
Chicken Saute with yogurt on top: This is highly recommended! I prefer the texture of this compared to the Kebap. I prefer the tenderness of the chicken
Yogurt Kebap: This was good 

Turkish Coffee: This was my first time having Turkish Coffee so I cannot compare. 
Turkish Tea: This was offered to us complimentary. It was really nice of them and I really enjoyed the warm tea after the meal

I was very satisfied with this visit as well. I'm really impressed that they remembered us. I know they reviewed my last review and must have taken my water comment to heart because they made sure to keep our water topped. 

This is a small business and they don't have a lot of service persons working so it is understandable that something like that can be missed. But I really appreciate the effort that everyone made to host us. I will continue to recommend this establishment! See you next time

name: Kaffe Crepe
categories: Food, Restaurants, Cafes, Creperies, Coffee & Tea
text:
WHAT A DELICIOUS MISTAKE!
Brief history of the crepe it was created by mistake by a 14 year old assistant.Nick and I stopped by at Kaffe Crepe after his flight landed. Naturally we were both famished. Kaffe is a charming and quaint place. There is a huge selection of crepes to chose from; breakfast, lunch, and dessert. We ordered  The Cookie Butter (Biscoff cookie spread & crumbs, banana, and vanilla sugar) Huevos Rancheros (cheese blend, eggs, green tomatillos sauce ,Avocado and choice of meat) and the Chicken, Pesto & Mushroom (Cheese blend, grilled chicken, pesto, mushrooms, roasted bell peppers, and spinach). You order/pay at the counter and they bring your food out to your table. We were surprised at how big the portions were! I was full half way through my savory crepe but had to make room for the sweet crepe. All crepes were exceptional. Will definitely be coming back. Bon appetite!

name: Sunshine Spice Bakery & Cafe
categories: Arts & Entertainment, Afghan, Shopping, Restaurants, Art Galleries, Food, Coffee & Tea, Bakeries, Arts & Crafts, Desserts
text:
After reading about this new Afghan Bakery in Boise and the delicious pastries they produced, we had to give it a try. The layout and decor was just as described by Michele R. The young ladies were just as she also described and were patient with our questions and inquiries.

We decide to do the eat and drink and then take home some of their goodies. We found they did Turkish coffee in the correct manner and style. A good caffeine kick and the deep taste and aroma of Turkish coffee. With our coffee, we shared a Croissant shaped pastry, but filled with jam. Wonderful! We also shared a Poppyseed Roll which was so light and delicious.

We decided to take home what turned out to be 3 boxes of pastries: Turkish Bagel, Afghan flat bread, another jam roll,  another poppyseed roll, 3 cookies, 2 Baklavas. and a jam donut (much like a Portuguese Florshe/donut). Dessert with tonight's dinner and breakfast tomorrow from all these goodies.

We asked about call in orders and they said a day ahead of time would be good. So when we want a dozen of their poppyseed rolls, that is what we will do.

We are sure that we will be upgrading them to a 5 star after another visit.

name: Donut Delight
categories: Donuts, Restaurants, Food
text:
Sooooo sorry for not doing this sooner! I guess I should explain why this place is amazing. I have noticed this place for years since I've been passing by here countless times. It wasn't until I started working out in West County in January and stopping close by for gas that I really started to think about stopping. And in my panic to not speed up my post collegiate swimming career weight gain, I held off on stopping in for far too long. That was until my temp position days were were coming to an end rather quickly and I thought I wouldn't be stopping at my trusty Mobil next door as often. Then lo and behold Stephen gets a full time job. Since then I have been in too many times to count.

The building must be a converted fast food restaurant that failed. They kept all the original seating and walls. Its, for use of a better word, "tits"! Reminds me of the Hardees we used to frequent way too often, that is across the street from good ole St. Ambrose. Takes me back... So I'm going to go with its an old Hardees. They even use the drive thru. I'v only gone through twice. I enjoy watching my donut being taken out of the case and taking a seat among the reitrees (if time permits) too much.

The biggest reason they are awesome. I didn't realize the coconut one was going to be 80 cents as opposed to the 50 cents that most of them are (the menu board always has me confused, I can be rather slow). So when I walked in with my four quarters for two donuts. I was met with a surprise. And then the friendly donut server girl met me with another. She told me to pay her back next time I came in! I really hope that means I'm a regular! Well I'll be seeing her Tuesday after I fill up my gas tank. Better start thinking about what to get them for Xmas...

Donuts I've had so far (I'll update on what I try or remember on subsequent visits)

Glazed, best glazed I have ever had besides Dukes/Sunrise (Alton), it is best when it has been sitting for just a little while, not fresh out of the glaze, but not come to room temp yet. room temp is good too
Coconut on white cake with vanilla frosting - heaven!
Blueberry 
Chocolate long john
Old fashioned log - kinda weird - perhaps a little too greasy - lips felt like I had put chapstick on - I will probably try it again though just to make sure
Devils food
White cake vanilla frosting - like knowing you belong in heaven but waiting in purgatory for your coconut - in other words, good

name: Vegan International Co. Kitchen & Market
categories: Desserts, Restaurants, Vegan, Food, Sandwiches, Halal, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Vegetarian
text: LOVE this vegan restaurant!!! The owners, Garnet and Jean, are such a lovely couple. They were so comfortable to talk with about our mutual love of being vegan and felt like we had known them for years. The food was amazingly delicious! I've always wanted to try a Jamaican patty, but have never found one that is vegan so I was thrilled to find they make some and theirs are wonderful! We also tried the curry chickpea patties and lentil soup and the flavors were perfect. We were short on time otherwise we would have tried the plate, but we will definitely be coming back numerous times. We took home the key lime cheesecake, blueberry muffins, carob muffins, and coconut cookie and they were all soooo delicious!!! Do yourself a favor and visit this sweet couple's kitchen. You will not be disappointed, whether you are vegan or not. :)

name: Sultn Mediterranean Restaurant
categories: Mediterranean, Restaurants, Middle Eastern
text:
This place is killing it on the review sites, and I don't feel compelled to dissent. There were two small dining rooms, and noise echoed. As with most Mediterranean, the mezze are where it's at. Hummus and falafel aren't hard to find, but they were fantastic here and were accompanied by a massive flatbread that might be the most delicious such bread I've ever had. Seriously, the subtly crisped exterior and the hint of sourness kept me coming back for more than I should have eaten.

I had a vegetable pillau rice as an entree, which came with a hearty mixture of spinach and kidney beans. Not as ecstatic of an experience as the bread, but I felt good about eating it.

text:

The permit was emailed to me a couple of days later.
Simple
Easy

name: Padrinos Mexican Restaurant
categories: Restaurants, Mexican, Cocktail Bars, Nightlife, Bars
text:
So wanted to try this because of all the 5 star reviews. It's Saturday nite. The room is one big noisy open area. No sound buffering and when a party of 12 came in we couldn't hear ourselves talking to one another. The place otherwise is cute and clean. We were waited on right away. The waitress didn't seem to know a lot about the menu. But she ran off to ask questions. 
I got the steak fajitas which were a very generous portion. My friend got a veggie quesadilla, also large portion. We both loved the food. Hot and fresh. Chips we're just ok. Guacamole was fresh/good . Salsa was too runny for our liking. Doesn't stay on the chip. 
The low score came from the end. They offered a discount for paying with cash, but instead ADDED it to our bill and also short changed us to boot. When we drew it to her attention she said their cash register has issues. What?  Then the bathroom was out of TP and hand towels. So, just overall not ideal. Sorry.

name: Williamsburg Cucina Caffe' e Bottega
categories: Food Trucks, Restaurants, Italian, Caterers, Event Planning & Services, Food
text:
Finally got to checkout this lovely food truck!

We ordered the caprese sandwich, Hamptons sandwich and the Nutella and chocolate croissant.

The pastrami, pickled vegetables and truffle mustard were a perfect combination; I loved the Hamptons Sandwich. The bread also did not get soggy, huge plus!

The burrata on the caprese sandwich was to die for. The bread also remained crisp and the arugula added some bitterness to balance the luscious burrata.

The Nutella croissant was delicious but I personally could have done without the whipped cream (that didn't stop me from finishing all though).

Overall, I would definitely eat from here again! Great job!

name: Sesami
categories: Japanese, Pan Asian, Restaurants, Korean, Chinese, Asian Fusion
text: I love the complexities of well thought out, intertwining  flavors and this customizable bowl certainly hit all the right notes. Just being a fan of the choose your own bowl style, I have to commend that each ingredient additively contributed to a deliciously combined experience. Aside from the visual and health appeal of multicolored topping, sauces, vegetables and meats, the bowl offers a lasting taste of freshness and comfort with every bite. Generously filled to the brim, you can sure to be full after this wonderful meal. Grab a side of their refreshing, in house made tea while you're at it to further complement your bowl! Would love to come here more often and it's definitely worth the hike even as someone who is coming from the city. The staff is wonderful too so you can be sure to have a pleasant stop by whether for lunch or for dinner. :)

name: Carlillos Cocina
categories: Bars, Mexican, Breakfast & Brunch, Restaurants, Nightlife
text:
GUYS. The hype is real at Carlillos. A true hidden gem with all the old school diner feels.  My husband and I came in for the first time on a Wednesday for breakfast.  There were only a few other people dining so there were plenty of seats.  I can imagine though this place being super packed on a Saturday.  

My go-to Mexican breakfasts are Chilaquiles or Chile Rellenos & Eggs.  Carlillos offers both.  So straight up Sophie's Choice. I found it super difficult to chose because I love both so much! I finally cut my limb and went with Chilaquiles.  I got it with chicken and green sauce. Husband got a chorizo and egg torta.  Which both came with rice, beans and pickled veggies.  All these components made up to one plated showpiece!  We watched our food being made and plated.  These guys behind the counter definitely know what they're doing.  It was like watching some kind of kitchen choreography.  

Both the chilaquiles and the torta were delicious! We were taken back by how much flavor each plate had! Portions were huge too! I only ate half of mine and took the other half to go.  My only complaint is that the rice was a little hard and under cooked.  Maybe an off day? 

I've already planned my future visit.  I'm going to order the Chile Rellenos.  And I'm also going to make sure I don't have to go to work after because the food here is so good it'll literally put ya azzz to sleep.

name: Kounter Kulture
categories: Korean, Asian Fusion, Salad, Japanese, Soup, Restaurants
text:
Kounter Kulture deserves their 5 star rating.  I have been there 3 times so far and each time I came away impressed by the service and, most importantly, the food. 

I have tried the salmon dish twice, one of the noodle dishes (sorry, I can't remember the name) and have had several buns.  They are all delicious.  

The menu is very limited.  What they do, they do well. 

The restaurant mostly operates as a take out operation as there is no indoor seating and just a table or two outside.  I'd recommend calling your order in ahead of time so it will be ready when you arrive.  

The prices here are above a normal take out restaurant but the quality is much higher and a lot of their ingredients are sourced locally.  

I am very glad I found this place especially now that I just moved a bit closer. Try it. You'll like it.

name: Gulfport Brewery and Eatery
categories: Breweries, Beer Gardens, Food, Nightlife, American (New), Restaurants
text:
Arrived here on a Monday early afternoon in October 2021. The location was very slow given that it was a Monday but we absolutely love that as it allowed us to just really unwind and relax. The location overall is a little quirky but in a good way. They do have indoor seating and they have large outdoor spaces were multiple groups could hang out without impeding on others. The food smells delicious we opted to just stick with something small and ended up with their hot boiled peanuts. The peanuts were delicious and had a great little hint of spice to them after a few.

I opted for the light beer and my husband opted for a amber ale. Both were delicious and we ended up getting another round while we hung out in the yard.

name: Caffe Ida
categories: Sandwiches, Food, Coffee & Tea, Restaurants, Italian
text: How selfish of me not to have written sooner.!   If you like authentic Italian, (yes, the old men, talking Italian, playing cards-type of Italian) then this is the place to go !  a simple menu, done well !  Breakfast sandwiches to die for, simple eggs, meat and cheese on a great soft, grilled roll that can easily feed 2.  I am a coffee snob, and every coffee drink is done as if I was at a cafe in Roma !   Sandwiches,soup and pastries are delish !  Took my Dad there today and we were offered a complimentary new summer dessert, Cafe Crema, a soft espresso whipped delight.  Today I saw the chicken cutlets fried up for sandwiches and they looked as good as Nona would make.  Worth the trip from anywhere !

text:
First time ordering. Husband in rehab & needed a meal because I didn't want to cook & didn't want fast food. My stepson & I ordered the potstickers, Rangoon, kabocha bisque, KFC, sweet potato gnocchi & the mini baguette.
Everything was delicious. Gnocchi were perfect- not gummy or dense. Rangoon with real lobster was amazing. It was a perfect meal ( with leftovers , woohoo) after a very tense week.
We are now spoiled. We will be back. Thank you Akar for a wonderful experience.

name: Spice Routes
categories: Restaurants, Sandwiches, Mediterranean, Middle Eastern, Soup
text:
I know Spice Routes from their long time participation in the St Pete Saturday Morning Market.  There is a LOT of great food at the Market.  Judys soup is one of the most iconic foods there. 

Every week is 4 different varieties.  I keep thinking that I've finally discovered my favorite, and then a new one comes a long that I like even better.  Every week I go home with a quart.  

Lots of the flavors are magnificent versions of traditional flavors, and then there's the ones that you've never heard of before.  Like 'African Ground Nut Stew'.  Sounds offbeat, but its wonderful.

If you like hearty soups, you HAVE to try these.

name: Petite Street
categories: Bartenders, Sandwiches, Event Planning & Services, Restaurants, Food, Caterers, Food Trucks, Beer, Wine & Spirits
text:
By far the best cocktails and bar service of any wedding I've experienced. If you care about quality drinks, Jeff and Angela are the people you want to work with. From initially meeting them at our cocktail tasting, we knew right away they were going to be fun and easy to work with. They are both highly skilled, organized and personable people. 

Not only do they strive for the best quality ingredients, they take into account every detail (beautiful garnish, proper amount of ice, no one waiting in line for a drink, etc) to ensure a flawless and exceptional drink service. We also liked that we were able to purchase our own alcohol so we could get the specific brands that we love. They told us exactly how much of everything to get and made it super easy to purchase.

It's clear that Jeff and Angela are passionate about serving excellent from-scratch cocktails. We would hire them again in a heartbeat!

name: Miss Rachel's Pantry
categories: Arts & Crafts, Food, Shopping, Food Delivery Services, Event Planning & Services, Cafes, Vegan, Restaurants, Caterers, Cooking Classes
text:
This place is SO GOOD! I was so excited to finally come here for my birthday!

My parents, brother, and I on a Friday evening. We had reserved a month ahead of time and paid $65 a person. I thought that was a very reasonable price for the amount of food we received + it included gratuity! 

We started our meal with these delicious biscuits + butter. Wow they were so good. It was hard not to eat 4 of them. They were the best biscuits I've ever had!

We then had Corn Chowder with Kaffir Lime Cornbread and it was incredible. Very creamy and flavorful. Next we had cold beets with ricotta, amazing as well. We then had Potato & Mozzarella stuffed Cappellacci Carbonara. I think this was course, they were like pasta dumplings! So so good! The final savory course was Black Pepper Glazed Seitan with horseradish aioli & Apple/caramelized onion chutney. I didn't know Seitan could taste so good. Perfectly seasoned and paired well with the roasted carrots on the plate. 

For dessert we had Blueberry Buttermilk Cake with Buttercream Frosting. It was A LOT of frosting but very sweet and satisfying. 

I would love to come back here someday! Seriously some of the best vegan food I've ever had.

name: Urban Fresh
categories: Vegan, Live/Raw Food, Food, Juice Bars & Smoothies, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch
text: Hands down my favorite place to eat in Tuscon! I visit Tucson for just under a month every year during the gem and mineral show, and this place is my go to. I visit these wonderful people almost every day for a fresh juice and usually grab at least one meal to eat on the spot and a second meal, wrap or veggie burger to snack on during the day. It's that good! You can tell that the owners put a lot of love and passion into their food! They never failed to deliver delicious and super healthy food to fuel me through the long days at gem show!  The entire staff are anyways helpful and happy! I highly recommend Urban Fresh to vegans, vegetarians and meat eats alike!
